21) Proj No. SCSE24-0022
Project Title Enhancing Tourist Safety: Introducing Voyager, a Com-prehensive Mobile Application for Informed and Secure Travel
Project Summary With the yearly increase of travelers around the world, tourist fatalities continue to rise. The findings reinforce industry trends from previous studies, implying that creating a tourist fatality database would significantly make preventive and educational plans to decrease the number of trauma-based tourist fatalities. As seen with many other studies, transportation-based fatalities were among the highest recorded with incidents. However, some studies concluded that water-based activities, explicitly swimming and boating, are now the largest cause of mortality reported. Nearly half of the fatalities recorded took place in Asian countries, followed by European and African countries. Out of the one billion tourists traveling each year globally, it is estimated that around 30% are either injured or become ill while traveling abroad. As the number of travel increases and the number of tourists’ activities expands, the number of incidents resulting in tourist fatalities will likely increase.

This proposed application allows crowds to share their experience of pleasure they had with a particular place or event and unfortunate incidents they faced with the geographical location to provide prevention and education for future travelers. Besides that, local people can provide more accurate information with geographical location to provide a better experience for visitors and share unfortunate incidents for previous visitors to prevent an educated traveler from avoiding such incidents.

The proposed system will focus only on Singapore and Sri Lanka, but the system should address this issue globally. The creation of tourist fatality databases has aided professionals in addressing issues that lead to tourist mortality. Future research investigating the effectiveness and success of any preventive measures to prevent tourist fatalities is also recommended.

Specific details:
(a) Design component

Design web and mobiile application
(b) Implementation component

Develop web and mobile applications

(a) Research component

Identify the Incidences and total fatalities based on following categories:
Seasonality: seasonal distribution of tourist fatalities between January to December
Domestic vs. international, and the location of incidences
Gender and Age Distribution
Activities: Water-based traumas, namely from swimming and boating, hiking, etc.


(b) Development component

The creation of tourist fatality databases
Supervisor Dr Owen Noel Newton Fernando

22) Proj No. SCSE24-0023
Project Title Catalyzing Content Generation and Automation: Empowering Diverse Written Content Creation through Generative AI
Project Summary This research delves into the transformative impact of large language models (LLMs) on content generation and automation. It explores how LLMs have revolutionized the creation of diverse written content through Generative AI applications. These models, exemplified by GPT-4, possess the remarkable ability to emulate various content styles, tones, and structures by drawing from extensive datasets and advanced natural language processing techniques. This transformative capability extends to generating articles, blog posts, social media captions, product descriptions, news reports, and more. Furthermore, LLMs contribute to content automation by generating content based on specific parameters or prompts, which has significant implications across industries like E-commerce.

Dataset Collection and Curation:
Gather a diverse and extensive dataset comprising text from various content genres, including articles, blogs, social media posts, product descriptions, and news reports.

Large Language Model Training:
Train large language models such as GPT-4 using the curated dataset to develop an understanding of diverse content styles and structures.

Content Generation Evaluation:
Evaluate the LLM's content generation capabilities using metrics like coherence, relevance, and human readability.
Conduct comparative analyses between LLM-generated content and content authored by humans to establish benchmarks.

This research aims to showcase the transformative potential of LLMs in content generation and automation, offering practical solutions across industries and domains. By training and evaluating these models, developing user-friendly interfaces, and creating applications for content automation, the study seeks to harness the capabilities of LLMs to produce coherent, relevant, and contextually appropriate written content.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Train large language models such as GPT-4 using the curated dataset to develop an understanding of diverse content styles and structures.

Conduct comparative analyses between LLM-generated content and content authored by humans to establish benchmarks.

(b) Development component
Develop applications and interfaces that facilitate content automation using LLMs.

Implement parameters and prompts to instruct LLMs in generating specific content types, such as product descriptions.

Design user-friendly interfaces that enable users to input content requirements and receive LLM-generated content.

26) Proj No. SCSE24-0027
Project Title Evaluation of Online Teaching Quality Based on Facial Expression Recognition
Project Summary In 21st-century society, with the rapid development of information technology, the scientific and technological strength of all walks of life is increasing, and the field of education has also begun to introduce high and new technologies gradually. Affected by the epidemic, online teaching has been implemented all over the world, forming an education model of “dual integration” of online and offline teaching. However, the disadvantages of online teaching are also obvious; that is, teachers cannot understand the students’ listening status in real time. This research proposes a deep learning-based approach using facial emotions to detect the real-time engagement of online learners. This can be done by analyzing the students’ facial expressions to classify their emotions throughout the online learning session.

Knowledge in ResNet-50, VGG19 and Inception-V3 experience required to complete this project.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Train a deep learning model, such as a convolutional neural network (CNN) or a deep neural network (DNN), to recognize and classify facial expressions into different emotions (e.g., happy, sad, engaged, confused).

To develop a deep learning-based system that can detect and classify students' emotions in real-time during online learning sessions.

To explore how monitoring facial expressions can provide insights into student engagement and comprehension.

To assess the impact of real-time emotion analysis on teaching effectiveness and student learning outcomes in online education.


(b) Development component

Create a user-friendly interface for both educators and students to access the emotion analysis results.

Ensure that the interface respects user privacy and provides actionable insights.

29) Proj No. SCSE24-0030
Project Title Enhancing Test Script Automation: Leveraging Large Language Models for SRS Document-Based Test Script Generation
Project Summary The research project aims to automate the process of generating test scripts from Software Requirement Specification (SRS) documents, leveraging the capabilities of advanced language models, specifically GPT-4 and PaLM-2. Project Title Learning to Generate Radiance Fields of Indoor Scenes
Project Summary We have a natural ability to understand and predict how the 3D world looks from different perspectives, even with limited observations. Our spatial reasoning comes from the mental models we form about the visual world over time. These models represent our beliefs about the most likely configurations of the world, and can be thought of as a probability distribution over the 3D world, called a prior. This project focuses on the development of model that learns priors over the 3D visual world, specifically realistic and unconstrained indoor scenes. The models use radiance fields to represent scenes and jointly model geometry and appearance while considering view-dependent effects.

Project Title Modelling connected extremes with graphical models
Project Summary Graphical models have been used to study social networks, bank connections, languages, biological functions and more. These methods also provide a means to identify causal factors and perform system dynamics modelling. A recent development looks at graphical models tailored for extremes such as extreme weather and extreme financial losses.

Graphical models have been used to study social networks, bank connections, languages, biological functions and more. These methods also provide a means to identify causal factors and perform system dynamics modelling. A recent development looks at graphical models tailored for extremes such as extreme weather and extreme financial losses.

This project explores the modelling, computational and practical benefits of this new approach. Example Research Questions to address:
(1) Are different causal factors identified in the extreme setting?
(2) How much computational benefit does a model based on extreme value theory provide by enabling analytical estimation as opposed to simulation-based estimation for extremes?
(3) Can these graphical models be used to simulate connected extreme events and assess risk?
(4) How might they be useful for evaluating mitigation strategies?

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
To start, we will conduct a literature review on graphical models and its connection to causal analysis. Next, we will identify the extensions made to tailor graphical models to extreme values. This will require some reading of bivariate extreme value theory.

(b) Development component
Focusing on a few case studies, we will build a graphical model and an extremal graphical model for each scenario. This will help to answer RQ 1. To address RQ 2, we can estimate probability of extremes (e.g. occurrences above a pre-defined threshold) via simulations of the fitted non-extremal model and through analytical results available for the fitted extremal model. Similar comparisons can be conducted to gain insights for RQ3 and 4.

Project Title Leveraging covariate space for grouping
Project Summary How do we make the most reasonable guess in the absence of data? In the domain of public health, for example, one may need to provide estimates of patient behaviour or disease prevalence for locations where measurements have not been taken. While spatial statistical methods may be useful for borrowing information from neighbouring locations with data, in some cases, direct neighbours may not be a good indicator due to huge differences in underlying covariates such as socio-economic factors or different public health policies across administrative borders. In such circumstances, can we turn to the covariate space to determine which neighbours may be most useful to inform prediction? In this project, we attempt to leverage covariate space to group neighbours for prediction.

Specific details:

(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

(b) Development component
In the second part, we will develop a procedure for matching unsampled locations with sampled locations. Using a simulation or case study, we will investigate changes in the predictive performance while varying parameters of the procedure such as the choice of covariates used for matching.

(b) Implementation component

In the first part of the project, we will conduct a literature review on key characteristics and summary descriptors of time series. We will also outline suitable clustering methods.

(b) Development component
Using simulation and/ case studies, we will study how different characteristics may be more or less important for clustering. By implementing different clustering methods for the time series, we will also see how the architecture of the methods influences clustering results.
Supervisor Dr Michele Nguyen
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only
Type Research & Development
Keywords Data Analytics
Machine Learning
51) Proj No. SCSE24-0052
Project Title Dynamic extreme value models and their applications
Project Summary Dynamic extreme value models have been developed for forecasting volcanic eruptions and financial risk. These utilise the peaks-over-threshold approach which focuses on the distribution of excesses (the amounts above a fixed threshold). In this project, we aim to build upon these works to expand either the modelling approach by for example, using a block maxima approach (i.e. focusing on the distribution of maximum or minimum values instead), or expanding the range of applications of the dynamic peaks-over-threshold model.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
In the first part of the project, we will review the extreme value modelling approaches including the peaks-over-threshold approach.

(b) Development component
Using the dynamic extreme value models developed for volcanic eruptions and financial forecasting as a starting point, we will either propose an adaptation based on alternative models for threshold exceedance or consider additional features to improve forecasts. A simulation or case study will be used to demonstrate the proposed methods.
Supervisor Dr Michele Nguyen
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only
Type Research & Development
Keywords Data Analytics
Machine Learning

67) Proj No. SCSE24-0068
Project Title Controllable Image Generation and Editing
Project Summary The spotlight on visual content generation has intensified in recent years, with its immense potential spanning across applications such as data augmentation, design, filmmaking, animation, gaming, AR/VR, and social media. This project sets out to pioneer the development of innovative algorithms for controllable image generation and editing, based on diffusion, GANs, and other cutting-edge generation frameworks. We will explore different types of control signals, such as text descriptions, reference images, box layouts, and style images, to control the image generation process. The candidates are required to have their GPU resources for deep network training (e.g., GTX 3080 or above).

69) Proj No. SCSE24-0070
Project Title Deep Learning Methods with Less Supervision
Project Summary Deep learning has achieved tremendous success for visual recognition in recent years. Deep network based methods are shown to outperform humans on the large-scale image classification dataset ImageNet. However, most deep learning methods focus on fully supervised learning tasks which usually require intensive hand labelling effort for creating training data. Especially for dense prediction tasks like semantic segmentation, it requires a large amount of accurate per-pixel annotations to construct training data for learning deep models, and thus needs expensive or even unaffordable human labelling effort and limits its real-world applications. To reduce the labelling effort, this project aims to develop effective weakly supervised learning and few-shot learning methods which require much less supervision information for visual recognition problems including semantic segmentation and object detection. The interested candidates should have their own GPU computation resources.

Specific details:
(a) Design component
Deep Convolutional Neural Networks

(b) Implementation component
Deep Convolutional Neural Networks

(a) Research component


(b) Development component
Supervisor A/P Lin Guosheng
Joint Industry Project/

71) Proj No. SCSE24-0072
Project Title Learning Deep Networks for 3D Scene Understanding
Project Summary 3D point cloud data are generated by 3D scanners such as LiDAR and RGB-D cameras. As 3D scanners are extensively applied in various applications including robotics, autonomous vehicles and augmented reality, there is an increasing research interest in developing effective visual understanding and recognition algorithms on 3D point cloud data. This project aims to develop accurate and efficient deep learning algorithms for visual scene understanding on point cloud data. Specifically, this project focuses on the tasks of object detection and semantic segmentation on point clouds. Typically, one point in point clouds is associated with different modalities or features, including 3D coordinate values, RGB color values, and sensor intensities. We will develop deep learning methods to jointly learn from different modalities to achieve accurate visual recognition and scene understanding. The developed methods will be evaluated on publicly available point cloud datasets such as ScanNet and SemanticKITTI. The interested candidates should have their own GPU computation resources.

Specific details:
(a) Design component
Deep Convolutional Neural Networks

(b) Implementation component
Deep Convolutional Neural Networks

(a) Research component


(b) Development component
Supervisor A/P Lin Guosheng
Joint Industry Project/

77) Proj No. SCSE24-0078
Project Title Developing efficient human-like memory systems
Project Summary Where and when did you go to the primary school? What did you see this morning when you went to the school? What did you have lunch yesterday? We humans have amazing memory systems. In contrast, AI systems still suffer from storing large amount of data efficiently. Students will be involved in research projects studying human memory systems. 88) Proj No. SCSE24-0089
Project Title Towards Robust Federated Learning
Project Summary With the proliferation of IoT and edge computing, federated learning is becoming more promising. When designing a federated learning system, one major challenge to consider is Byzantine Fault Tolerance (BFT). A malicious participant could inject poisoning data or gradient to compromise the integrity of the final model, causing performance degradation or backdoor injection. In this project, we will perform comprehensive evaluations over existing Byzantine attacks, and design new attack techniques. Meanwhile, we will also consider and test different BFT algorithms and come up with better solutions.

In this project, you will explore, design and implement robust federated deep learning algorithms and systems. The goal is to defeat strong Byzantine attacks, while maintaining high performance. You will conduct comprehensive evaluations with state-of-the-art deep learning tasks and applications in a distributed way.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

We consider both attacks and defenses in this project. For the attacks, we consider different goals: (1) accuracy degradation (2) backdoor injection. We also consider different attack techniques, including (1) poisoning the dataset, (2) poisoning the gradients. For the defenses, we consider different approaches: (1) malicious gradient detection; (2) statistical data processing, etc.

(b) Development component
Supervisor Ast/P Zhang Tianwei
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		URECA-FYP

Type Research & Development
Keywords Artificial Intelligence

108) Proj No. SCSE24-0109
Project Title Software Defined Network-on-Chip (4)
Project Summary As the number of cores integrated on a single chip increases, Network-on-Chip (NoC) becomes a widely-adopted communication paradigm for multi-core/many-core systems due to its high performance, flexibility and scalability. Nevertheless, the performance of such communication backbone is limited by two issues. The hop-by-hop transmission results in time-consuming long-distance communication, especially when the network size grows. The network contention among communication pairs with shared links results in huge delay and drastically degrades the NoC performance, especially when the communication volume increases. To eliminate or decrease the latency caused by long-distance and contention, software-defined NoCs can customize the NoC intercommunication architecture to adapt to the application and maximize the total system performance. The objective of this project is to study software-defined NoC architectures.

Specific details:
(a) Design component

(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Study software-defined NoC;
Compare it with state-of-the-art designs;
Advanced: explore the heterogeneity of processor cores.

(b) Development component

1. Build a software-defined NoC simulator;
2. Conduct experiments to verify the performance.
Supervisor A/P Liu Weichen
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Hardware & Software (Mostly Hardware)
Type Research & Development
Keywords Computer Architecture
System on-Chip
Hardware Acceleration
High-Performance Computing
Real-Time / Embedded Systems
109) Proj No. SCSE24-0110
Project Title Cache Coherence and Network-on-Chip (4)
Project Summary We will study the cache coherence protocols (CCP) for multiprocessor systems. The performance of CCPs are critical to scalable architectures. It is determined by both the CCP design and the underlining interprocessor communication architecture, and their efficiency. Network-on-Chip (NoC) is a scalable communication infrastructure, which could be optimized for the purpose of supporting CCPs in high performance. The study of the interaction between CCP and NoC will be a focus of this project with possible optimizations.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Survey and compare different CCPs;
Model and benchmark the NoC communication traffic due to CCPs;
Optimize the CCP and NoC combination for performance;
Advanced: explore the heterogeneity of processor cores.

(b) Development component

Implement the existing CCPs and simulate the traffic in NoC simulators;
Conduct experiments to showcase the optimization of CCP and NoC combination for performance improvement;
Supervisor A/P Liu Weichen
Joint Industry Project/

110) Proj No. SCSE24-0111
Project Title Cache Coherence and Network-on-Chip (3)
Project Summary We will study the cache coherence protocols (CCP) for multiprocessor systems. The performance of CCPs are critical to scalable architectures. It is determined by both the CCP design and the underlining interprocessor communication architecture, and their efficiency. Network-on-Chip (NoC) is a scalable communication infrastructure, which could be optimized for the purpose of supporting CCPs in high performance. The study of the interaction between CCP and NoC will be a focus of this project with possible optimizations.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Survey and compare different CCPs;
Model and benchmark the NoC communication traffic due to CCPs;
Optimize the CCP and NoC combination for performance;
Advanced: explore the heterogeneity of processor cores.

(b) Development component

Implement the existing CCPs and simulate the traffic in NoC simulators;
Conduct experiments to showcase the optimization of CCP and NoC combination for performance improvement;

111) Proj No. SCSE24-0112
Project Title Software Defined Network-on-Chip (3)
Project Summary As the number of cores integrated on a single chip increases, Network-on-Chip (NoC) becomes a widely-adopted communication paradigm for multi-core/many-core systems due to its high performance, flexibility and scalability. Nevertheless, the performance of such communication backbone is limited by two issues. The hop-by-hop transmission results in time-consuming long-distance communication, especially when the network size grows. The network contention among communication pairs with shared links results in huge delay and drastically degrades the NoC performance, especially when the communication volume increases. To eliminate or decrease the latency caused by long-distance and contention, software-defined NoCs can customize the NoC intercommunication architecture to adapt to the application and maximize the total system performance. The objective of this project is to study software-defined NoC architectures.

Specific details:
(a) Design component

(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Study software-defined NoC;
Compare it with state-of-the-art designs;
Advanced: explore the heterogeneity of processor cores.

(b) Development component

1. Build a software-defined NoC simulator;
2. Conduct experiments to verify the performance.
Supervisor A/P Liu Weichen
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No

Type Research & Development

116) Proj No. SCSE24-0117
Project Title Column based pruning for efficient LSTM
Project Summary With the development of deep learning, deep neural network models become deeper and deeper to achieve higher model accuracy. These models are not able to be deployed to embedded devices with limited resources. To tackle this problem, model pruning are developed to reduce the model size with little accuracy loss. Meanwhile, the pruned models become sparser and stored in sparse matrix formats. General processors like CPUs and GPUs are not efficient to execute these sparse operations. Thus, FPGAs have gained significant attention to perform these jobs. This project will explore the training method and refine the pruning method in order to design more efficient FPGA-based deep neural network accelerators.

Specific details:
(a) Design component

Design the training method to the pruned model.

(b) Implementation component

1. Implement the iterative training method to achieve the target accuracy.
2. Refine the pruning strategy if the accuracy could not be achieved.
3. (Optionally) Design the hardware accelerator.

(a) Research component


(b) Development component

117) Proj No. SCSE24-0118
Project Title Federated learning on heterogeneous edge devices (1)
Project Summary Federated learning has been proven promising in training deep neural networks with limited training data, which employs multiple devices to train a common deep neural network. In many cases, the data owned by different clients are private and cannot be shared with other clients, such as the users’ financial information from different banks. In federated learning, there is a server and multiple clients, the server is responsible for coordinating different clients. First, the server offloads a deep neural network to all clients, then each client starts to train the network with their own data without sharing the data with other clients. Finally, all clients upload the training information, such as gradients, to the server and the server integrates this information into the model for higher performance.

However, federated learning on edge devices is more complex since different clients possess different computing resources (i.e. memory and processors). It is still an open problem to modify and adjust the model based on the hardware constraints. This project will investigate the feasibility of using existing model compression techniques to modify the networks according to the hardware, such that we can reduce the resource consumption and boost the performance of the training process.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

1. Understand and research different techniques on federated learning
2. Understand model compression techniques (pruning, quantization, etc.)
(Advanced: explore the acceleration using a neural engine in an Android/iOS smartphone processor chip.)

(b) Development component

1. Implement different model compression algorithms
2. (Optionally) Integrate compression algorithms into federated learning
Supervisor A/P Liu Weichen

120) Proj No. SCSE24-0121
Project Title Evaluating Resource Allocation Algorithms in Clouds
Project Summary In modern data intensive computing, it is increasingly common for jobs to be executed in a distributed fashion across multiple machine clusters or datacenters to take advantage of data locality. Given the limited amount of resources available at each cluster or datacenter, the jobs inherently compete for resources with each other. Therefore, it is essential to design fair and efficient algorithms for sharing resources among concurrently running distributed jobs. Distributed jobs with parallel tasks have salient characteristics such as they do not need to acquire resources from various clusters or datacenters simultaneously in any fixed proportions and a job is completed only when all of its tasks are finished. These characteristics introduce new research challenges to job scheduling. The objective of this project is to analyze a real job trace from production systems such as Google and Alibaba and evaluate various job scheduling algorithms using the trace. If possible, the student will also design new algorithms to improve the job scheduling efficiency.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Analyze a real job trace and evaluate various job scheduling algorithms using the trace.

(b) Development component

Design and implement new algorithms to improve the job scheduling efficiency.
Supervisor A/P Tang Xueyan
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No

122) Proj No. SCSE24-0123
Project Title Evaluating Virtual Machine Allocations in Clouds
Project Summary Cloud computing provides on-demand shared resources on the pay-as-you-go basis. It is envisioned to be a promising and dominant computing model in IT infrastructures. Resource allocation is a fundamental issue faced by cloud providers, which aims at meeting the computational demands of customers with the minimum amount of cloud resources. Specifically, the cloud provider needs to assign the virtual machines requested by customers to the physical servers in its data centers while minimizing the number of physical servers needed or used. This can be modeled as a bin packing problem which is a combinatorial optimization problem. In the bin packing problem, given a set of items, the target is to pack the items into a minimum number of bins while guaranteeing that the aggregate size of the items in each bin does not exceed the bin capacity. In a cloud system, the virtual machines and physical servers can be mapped to the items and bins respectively. The objective of this project is to analyze a virtual machine allocation trace from the Microsoft Azure service and evaluate various virtual machine packing algorithms using the trace. If possible, the student will also design new algorithms to improve the virtual machine packing efficiency.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Analyze a virtual machine allocation trace from the Microsoft Azure service and evaluate various virtual machine packing algorithms using the trace.

(b) Development component

Design and implement new algorithms to improve the virtual machine packing efficiency.
Supervisor A/P Tang Xueyan

Project Title Protecting Neural Networks from Adversarial Attacks
Project Summary While a number of solutions for fast decisioning and inferencing on neural networks have been proposed in recent times, training a network remains a difficult task, often consuming days. The goal of this project is to set up a framework using OpenTPU and benchmarking the training time for various datasets. Subsequently, the training process needs to be optimised through batch-processing, hardware implementation, dynamic network tuning or a combination of the above.

131) Proj No. SCSE24-0132
Project Title Efficient Multi-Objective Peer-to-Peer Federated Learning
Project Summary Neural networks have become tremendously successful in recent times due to large computing power and availability of tagged datasets for various applications. Training these networks is computationally demanding and often requires proprietary datasets. Therefore, it is of major interest for unauthorised users to obtain the pre-trained models and sell it to third party for a premium. Watermarking is an effective way to prevent such usage. Although watermarking is an well known technique for IP ownership in several domains, establishing these techniques for neural networks will require careful study of adversarial models as well as practical usage of a model for the entire life cycle of it, including compression and transfer learning. The goal of this project is to study an existing watermarking technique proposed recently in [1,2], in terms of resilience, especially when the network size is small, and/or exhaustive weight perturbations are attempted.

Project Title Building an AIoT system emulator with Zephyr and QEMU
Project Summary An Internet of Things (IoT) system consists of a considerable number of networked heterogeneous nodes with different sensing, computation, and storage capabilities. For example, a smart home may be installed with tiny embedded sensors (e.g., temperature, humidity, and motion sensors), smart appliances (smart lights, wash machines, TVs, etc), smart power supplies (smart plugs, power outlets, household meters), and residents’ computing devices (smartphones, laptops, personal cloud). This project aims to design a middleware to support collaborative information processing in an IoT system. On top of a conceptual IoT system with smartphones, laptops, Raspberry Pis, tiny kMote sensors, we will use Java and C programming languages to create a framework such that the IoT application developers can easily define and plug in new signal/information processing modules, create an information processing pipeline based on selected modules, and specify which nodes execute which modules and how information are exchanged over the home-area network. In this Part-I project, we will develop a tool to visualize the run-time status of an IoT simulator.

Specific details:
(a) Design component

structure design of the middleware, design of messaging protocols, design of collaborative processing specification; design a tool to visualize the run-time status of an IoT simulator

(b) Implementation component

166) Proj No. SCSE24-0168
Project Title Modern Solvers for Automated Cryptanalysis
Project Summary Cryptanalysis is the science of breaking ciphers, usually involving a mix of mathematics and computer science. Analyzing existing ciphers is a very important task as we built our everyday life on the security of these primitives, which secure countless applications from the Internet, to banking, critical systems, telecommunications, etc...

While very important to improve our trust in current designs, cryptanalysis is a very tedious task, often done by humans. In the past decade, there has been an effort to automatize the cryptanalysis process as much as possible, using mathematical modeling and state-of-the-art solvers for useful problems such as SAT, Mixed-Integer Linear Programming (MILP) or Constraint Programming (CP).

The goal of this FYP is to study the applicability of such solvers to model some new state-of-the-art cryptanalysis methods, and therefore help in assessing the security of real cryptographic primitives.

In this project, you will:
1- Work in a competitive research environment.
2- Gather knowledge about two hot topics: cryptography and mathematical modeling.
3- In case of promising results, possibility to submit your work to a cryptography conference.
4- Learn how to use state-of-the-art solvers for SAT, Mixed-Integer Linear Programming (MILP) or Constraint Programming (CP) problems.

Specific details:
Supervisor Prof Peyrin Thomas
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only
Type Research & Development
Keywords Cyber Security
167) Proj No. SCSE24-0169
Project Title Scaling Explainable AI with Algorithmic Improvements
Project Summary Deep Neural Networks (DNNs) offer exceptional performance in a variety of difficult domains, but lack of robustness, explainability, etc. (due to their large complexity) is problematic.

We proposed a novel architecture called "Truth Table Deep Convolutional Neural Networks" or TTnets, which seems to be very promising for explainability/verification in many real-life scenarios. This architecture uses internally only small "truth-tables", which can be transformed after training into SAT equations.

We would like to remove one of the current existing lock with regards to TTnets scalability. Indeed, as of today, TTnets has been shown to work very well for small/medium image datasets such as MNIST or CIFAR10, using truth-table size of n = 12. The truth-tables in TTnets are then transformed into SAT equations using the classical Quine McCluskey algorithm (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quine\OT1\textendashMcCluskey_algorithm), which gives an optimally compact SAT representation of the truth-table.

For larger truth-table size (n = 48), we already confirmed that TTnets gets very good accuracy on larger datasets (such as ImageNET), but extracting the SAT equations from the truth-table using the Quine McCluskey algorithm is untractable with this size of n (the running time of the algorithm grows exponentially with the number of variables). Therefore the goal of this project is to consider:

- fast heuristic algorithms to transform a truth-table into a SAT equation (maybe not optimal), instead of getting the optimally compact representation from the Quine McCluskey algorithm. Some heuristics (like the ESPRESSO algorithm) already exist.

- modifying the truth-table values to make the Quine McCluskey algorithm or existing heuristics run faster even on large n

Specific details:
Supervisor Prof Peyrin Thomas
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only
Type Research & Development
Keywords Artificial Intelligence
Machine Learning
168) Proj No. SCSE24-0170
Project Title New model architectures for machine learning interpretability
Project Summary We have developed in NTU a very new neural network architecture so-called Truth Table Deep Convolutional Neural Networks or TTnets, which seems to be very promising for many real-life scenarios. They can be seen as compressed neural networks based on small lookup tables and they allow the transformation of the inference into a small system of SAT equations after learning. Thus, they are very well suited for example in constrained environments such as embedded systems, mobile phones, etc., and present other interesting properties for verifiability and interpretability. Preliminary studies show that TTnets are very simple NNs (easier to interpret and work with), while still providing a good accuracy.

The goal of this project is to explore the interpretability aspect of TTnets. The student will apply models based on the TTnet architecture to small real-life datasets that are well-suited for interpretability measures. We expect TT-nets to perform better than state-of-the-art on interpretability: https://papers.nips.cc/paper/2021/file/eaa32c96f620053cf442ad32258076b9-Paper.pdf

The candidate is expected to have some experience with machine learning. The project will be supervised by Prof. Thomas Peyrin.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component


(b) Development component

Project Title Green/Energy-efficient Deep Learning (hardware)
Project Summary We have developed in NTU a very new neural network architecture so-called Truth Table Deep Convolutional Neural Networks or TTnets, which seems to be very promising for many real-life scenarios. They can be seen as compressed neural networks based on small lookup tables. Thus, they are very well suited for example in constrained environments such as embedded systems, mobile phones, etc. Preliminary studies show that TTnets are very simple NNs (easier to interpret and work with), while still providing a good accuracy.

170) Proj No. SCSE24-0172
Project Title Green/Energy-efficient Deep Learning (software)
Project Summary We have developed in NTU a very new neural network architecture so-called Truth Table Deep Convolutional Neural Networks or TTnets, which seems to be very promising for many real-life scenarios. They can be seen as compressed neural networks based on small lookup tables. Thus, they are very well suited for example in constrained environments such as embedded systems, mobile phones, etc., but are also very efficient for parallel multi-client inference on cloud servers, without using GPUs.

The goal of this project is to explore the energy consumption and cost savings aspects of TTnets, which we believe should surpass the state-of-the-art. The student will design, implement, optimize and test TTnets models on software (high end CPUs), with the goal of reduced energy/power consumption and inference cost.

The candidate is expected to have a good experience in implementation optimization. The project will be supervised by Prof. Thomas Peyrin.

197) Proj No. SCSE24-0198
Project Title Performance Optimization of LLM Inference
Project Summary The cost of LLM inference is high in real-world applications. For example, employing Qwen-72B requires at least 4x NVIDIA A100 GPUs. We are building performance benchmarking to evaluate various inference frameworks and optimization techniques. In this task, based on applications of LLM inference, you will either minimize the cost (e.g., number of GPUs used) for given performance requirements (e.g., latency and throughput); or maximize the performance (e.g., throughput) for given hardware resources. The ultimate goal of the task is to improve the performance of LLM inference, and reduce the total cost of ownership (TCO) for LLM applications.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Investigate the latest advancements in model compression, quantization, and pruning specifically tailored for large language models. Analyze their impact on inference performance, including latency and throughput, and compatibility with various hardware platforms. Explore novel scheduling and load-balancing algorithms that can further enhance the efficiency of resource usage during LLM inference.

(b) Development component

Build a prototype toolkit that integrates the researched optimization techniques. This toolkit should be capable of analyzing an LLM's structure and the target hardware's specifications to recommend and apply the most effective optimizations automatically. Validate the toolkit's effectiveness through rigorous testing across diverse real-world LLM applications, documenting improvements in performance and reductions in total cost of ownership.
Supervisor Ast/P Shuhao Zhang
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No

Type Research & Development
Keywords Artificial Intelligence
High-Performance Computing

Project Title Adaptive Approximate Matrix Multiplication for Efficient Join Operations in Big Data Analytics
Project Summary This Final Year Project (FYP) aims to explore and innovate within the realm of database management systems by integrating Approximate Matrix Multiplication (AMM) algorithms to optimize join operations, a cornerstone of data analytics. Leveraging the team's library of AMM algorithms, this project seeks to address the computational challenges posed by large-scale data processing, emphasizing efficiency, scalability, and accuracy. Through a comprehensive approach combining research and development, the project will contribute to advancing big data analytics, offering a novel solution that bridges the gap between theoretical algorithms and practical database applications.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Conduct extensive benchmarking of existing AMM algorithms against traditional join methods across diverse datasets to establish baseline performance, scalability, and accuracy metrics.

Investigate and develop an adaptive selection mechanism that intelligently chooses the most appropriate AMM algorithm based on specific characteristics of the data and the requirements of the query.

(b) Development component

Develop a comprehensive framework that incorporates the adaptive algorithm selection mechanism, integrating it with the existing library of AMM algorithms for efficient join operations.

Validate the developed framework against real-world datasets and queries, fine-tuning the system for optimal performance and usability in practical applications.

Project Title Adaptive AKNN: Online Ingestion and Real-time Data Processing for Dynamic Environments
Project Summary This project aims to redefine the efficiency and applicability of Approximate K Nearest Neighbor (AKNN) algorithms in environments where data is continuously ingested in real-time. It challenges the traditional assumption that vector data remains static, proposing instead a framework where AKNN algorithms adapt to dynamic data ingestion without compromising on retrieval performance or ingestion efficiency. This work will involve both innovative research and the practical development of an enhanced AKNN system designed for the complexities of real-world data patterns.

(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

(b) Development component

201) Proj No. SCSE24-0202
Project Title Optimizing Sliding Window Joins for Streaming Data on Multicore Systems
Project Summary This project focuses on reimagining the implementation of sliding window joins (SWJ) for data streams, specifically addressing the challenges posed by existing algorithms when deployed on modern multicore architectures. The limitations of current SWJ approaches include inefficient management of continuous data updates, underutilization of multicore capabilities, and a lack of adaptability to varying data workloads. The goal is to design a scalable, adaptive SWJ algorithm that leverages the full potential of multicore processors while minimizing overhead and dynamically adjusting to changing input workloads.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Review literature to identify gaps in existing algorithms and explore potential multicore optimization techniques, including parallel processing strategies and adaptive workload distribution methods.

(b) Development component

Implement a prototype that incorporates innovative data management and processing techniques optimized for multicore environments. Evaluate performance improvements in terms of throughput, latency, and resource utilization across diverse data streams.
Supervisor Ast/P Shuhao Zhang
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only

Project Title StateFlow: Scalable State Management in NFV-Enabled Service Function Chains
Project Summary This project tackles the complexities of state management in network function virtualization (NFV) environments, particularly within service function chains (SFCs) that are stateful. NFV introduces a paradigm shift in network infrastructure, offering dynamic service orchestration but also presenting new challenges in maintaining state consistency and scalability. The project aims to develop a scalable solution, "StateFlow," to efficiently manage state across stateful SFCs, ensuring seamless service delivery and performance scalability.

Specific details:

(b) Implementation component

(b) Development component

204) Proj No. SCSE24-0205
Project Title FortiStream: Enhancing Fault Tolerance in Transactional Stream Processing Engines
Project Summary This project addresses the crucial challenge of improving fault tolerance in Transactional Stream Processing Engines (TSPEs) [1], which are vital for real-time applications requiring transactional semantics. Despite the focus on performance, TSPEs struggle with maintaining service continuity in the face of system failures and power outages. This project proposes developing "FortiStream," a framework designed to enhance the resilience of TSPEs without compromising their performance, by integrating advanced fault tolerance mechanisms tailored for the unique data dependencies and transactional requirements of TSPEs.

See [1]: https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00778-023-00814-z

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Conduct a thorough review of literature and existing systems to pinpoint why current approaches fall short in TSPE contexts, focusing on data dependency complexities.

(b) Development component

Develop a prototype that incorporates innovative techniques for data recovery, transaction consistency, and system stability. Benchmark the solution against existing TSPEs to demonstrate its effectiveness in ensuring fault tolerance while maintaining or enhancing performance.

205) Proj No. SCSE24-0206
Project Title StreamSpec: Benchmarking Transactional Stream Processing Systems
Project Summary This project seeks to establish a comprehensive understanding and benchmarking framework for Transactional Stream Processing (TSP) systems. Given the diversity in functionalities and performance levels among existing TSP systems, there's a clear need for standardized definitions, query sets, and primitive operations crucial for TSP. The project will first delineate precise definitions for TSP queries and identify essential primitive operations. Subsequently, it will explore various implementations and optimizations for these primitives, culminating in the creation of a benchmark framework to assess the effectiveness of TSP systems comprehensively.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Conduct a detailed review of existing TSP systems, identifying gaps in functionalities and performance variations.

(b) Development component

Prototype the "StreamSpec" framework, applying it to various TSP systems to validate its effectiveness in providing meaningful performance assessments.

206) Proj No. SCSE24-0207
Project Title ASJoin: Energy-Efficient Stream Processing on Asymmetric Multicore Processors
Project Summary This FYP focuses on optimizing stream window join algorithms for the asymmetric multicore processors (AMP) prevalent in IoT devices, like the ARM big.LITTLE architecture. Traditional stream processing algorithms, designed with cloud data centers in mind, fall short on AMPs due to their symmetric processor assumption and disregard for energy efficiency. The project proposes "ASJoin," an innovative algorithm that improves performance and reduces energy consumption by leveraging AMP characteristics. It includes designing AMP-aware strategies for runtime prediction, data distribution, and minimizing memory-intensive operations, thereby enhancing in-situ streaming analytics in IoT devices.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Review existing literature on stream processing in cloud and edge computing, focusing on energy consumption patterns and performance bottlenecks in AMP environments.

(b) Development component

Implement the algorithm, incorporating AMP-aware optimization techniques. Conduct extensive testing to empirically validate ASJoin's energy savings and performance gains over current state-of-the-art solutions.
Supervisor Ast/P Shuhao Zhang

Project Title Protecting Deep Learning Algorithms from Model Theft
Project Summary Deep learning algorithms are now widely used in many edge computing systems. The privacy of the deep learning algorithms can be compromised by attackers who can analyze the execution patterns to reverse engineer the algorithms. Such attack is known as model theft. This project aims to develop runtime methods on embedded systems that can dynamically obfuscate the execution patterns to protect the system from model theft.

Project Title Collaborative Visual Localization System for Search and Rescue Operations
Project Summary Agents deployed for search and rescue operations need to collaboratively map the environment as they explore unknown areas. Their positions in the map must also be communicated to a centralized supervisor who can then broadcast the necessary instructions to the agents. The core technology for achieving this is visual localization and mapping. The aim of this project is to develop an edge-server framework where the agents run visual localization and local mapping at the edge (such as a wearable device), and communicate information to a centralized server that generates a global map. The server also runs algorithm for effective search and rescue operations, and broadcast instructions to the agents.

236) Proj No. SCSE24-0237
Project Title Beat Repeat – A mobile game to learn rhythmic beat patterns
Project Summary This project requires the design and development of a mobile app game that is able to easily create different rhythmic beat patterns, play it on the mobile phone and automatically evaluate how well the player can subsequently repeat the beat by tapping on the table or articulating with his or her voice. The app will capture in real-time, the sound input, analyse it rhythmic components and compute a score that will measure how closely the compute generated rhythmic beat was repeated by the player. The goal is to design an engaging app that can progressively teach someone to imitate more and more complex beat rhythms through a gamified approach.

241) Proj No. SCSE24-0242
Project Title Explainable Deep Learning for Time-series Medical Data Predictions
Project Summary Deep Learning (DL) has been at the forefront of Artificial Intelligence research in recent decades. Whilst there exists an exponential increase in computational power and deep learning performance a notable caveat in the development of DL methods is the lack of interpretability for predictions produced by these complex models. Thereby, recent advances in the field of Explainable Artificial Intelligence (XAI) have catered methods to increase explainability and understanding of the model predictions given by DL methods.
DL methods are often applied in the Medical Domain, for example this could be to facilitate medical decision making or improve patient specific medical outcomes. Naturally, due to the sensitivity of the domain; XAI is fundamental to help understand the given predictions by DL models.
Medical data can often present itself in a time-series format; unfortunately, modern XAI techniques deal with instance based explainability and do not conform to the time-series nature of the data presented; instead treating instances independently. Hereby, we propose that the student focuses on the application of DL methods to time-series data using method(s) such as Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs) and Neural Ordinary Differential Equations (Neural ODE’s) and in doing so, develop and model-specific XAI methods to interpret respective time-series application model outcomes.

253) Proj No. SCSE24-0259
Project Title Causation versus correlation: when does it matter?
Project Summary Shark attacks and the sales of ice cream are highly correlated but does selling more ice cream lead to higher probabilities of being attacked by a shark?

The above example illustrates the difference between correlation (observed co-movement of variables) and causation (direct links or cause-and-effect relationship). While many statistical and machine learning methods rely on correlation between variables to select features and create predictions, there has been a recent interest in models based on causality. Causal feature selection has been seen to produce smaller features sets in situations where the response variable is correlated with many features but directly caused by relatively few. This has several benefits including a lower risk of overfitting and better model interpretability.

In this project, we want to examine causal feature selection methods and contrast that to classical correlation-based methods. Through simulation experiments and real-life examples, we want to investigate when causal-based methods improve predictions.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
To start, we will conduct a literature review on feature selection methods (correlation-based and causality-based). Next, we will identify some base models on which we can implement and compare the feature selection methods.

(b) Development component
To test different scenarios, we will simulate data for correlated but not causal variables, and causal variables under different modelling assumptions. With this data, we will compare the prediction performance of models fitted by causal and correlation-based feature selection methods. Next, we will apply the methods to real-life data to check their practical implications.
Supervisor Dr Michele Nguyen
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only
Type Research & Development
Keywords Data Analytics
Graph Theory

Project Title Evaluating the impact of policies with network models
Project Summary Network or graphical models use the relationships between variables to simulate scenarios and make predictions. These are extensively used to model transportation systems, manufacturing processes, biological systems, telecommunication and more. Recently, a Generalized Network Autoregressive (GNAR) model has proposed to model time series observations recorded at different nodes of a network. For example, with time series data on trade, we can establish links by the degree of export trade between countries and use a GNAR to project future trade trends.

In this project, we want to investigate the forecasting capabilities of the GNAR model to conduct scenario analysis and inform decisions. With several real-life examples, we will compare different methods of implementing scenarios through for example, adjusting weights and incorporating covariates.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
To start, we will conduct a literature review on generalized network autoregressive models and learn how to implement the GNAR R package. We will also decide on key real-life case studies and gather time series data.

(b) Development component
For each real-life case study, we will fit GNARs with different modelling assumptions and compare the forecasting accuracies. Then, we will simulate the impact of different decisions on the network by varying aspects of the fitted GNARs.

265) Proj No. SCSE24-0271
Project Title Weighted model calibration and its limits
Project Summary In the Environmental Sciences, complex physical models are used to simulate and study natural phenomenon like volcanic eruption. Cost functions such as mean square error are often used to calibrate these models with field data. These functions, however, assume that the field observations are independent and equally important even though there is spatial dependence and additional observations near existing points do not provide as much information on the system as those elsewhere. To address this issue, weighted calibration based on spatial conditional information (CI) has been proposed.

In this project, we want to test the limits of this weighted calibration. At what point does the CI-informed weights not make sense? How can we improve the robustness of the method? Through simulation studies with spatial models, we can investigate various factors including correlated parameters, model misspecification, non-Gaussianity and more.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
To start, we will conduct a literature review on model calibration with loss functions (weighted and unweighted) and the geostatistical model. In this context, we can establish the link between weighted calibration, full likelihood-based estimation, pairwise likelihood estimation and marginal estimation.

(b) Development component
Using simulated data and simple real-life applications, we can test the weighted calibration approach with unweighted calibration in different scenarios. For example, with model misspecification, we can consider different spatial covariance/variogram structures. The aim of these experiments is to develop some guidances/list of things to check for the user to decide and implement weighted calibration over unweighted calibration.
Supervisor Dr Michele Nguyen
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only
Type Research & Development
Keywords Data Analytics
Machine Learning

268) Proj No. SCSE24-0274
Project Title Quantifying Combinatorial Capabilities of Image-generating AI
Project Summary In the past few years, deep neural networks have obtained the ability to generate realistic images that are difficult to differentiate from real images. The user can control the output using a textual command, such as "draw a box with a blue ball inside". Notable examples include DALL-E 2, Stable Diffusion, Midjourney, etc.

However, such networks often suffer from inability to understand and follow commands that involve combination of spatial relations and objects. For example, given the command "draw a box with a blue ball inside", they often can draw a box and a ball but the spatial relation depicted is often incorrect.

In this project, the student will evaluate the degree to which different models can follow verbal commands regarding spatial relations of two or more objects.

The tasks of this project include:

- Programmatically control a 3D engine such as Unity or Blender to create visual scenes involving objects. This will create a training set for the second step.

- Finetune an off-the-shelf object detection and depth detector to automatically detect spatial relations from the visual scenes.

- Create an automatic evaluation metric for existing image-generating networks.

This is a difficult project. The student should have some fundations in neural networks. Alternatively, the student should be willing to learn substantial amount of new knowledge.

Specific details:
(a) Design component

269) Proj No. SCSE24-0275
Project Title Extracting Event Knowledge from Pretrained Language Models Such as ChatGPT
Project Summary In the past few years, a major driver for performance improvements of neural networks, especially those that process natural language, is the rapid increase in their size. Large networks trained on gigantic text datasets, such as ChatGPT, have demonstrated excellent performance on a large number of tasks.

Intuitively, these neural networks possess enormous amount of knowledge in their parameters, but it is difficult to extract the knowledge in a human-understandable form and to quantify exactly what kind of event knowledge exists in such networks.

In this project, the student will attempt to design different types of textual queries, known as "prompts", which can extract event knowledge from pretrained language models. For example, one may ask the neural network "what would Alice typically do after she wakes up in the morning", in order to gather an event sequence or an event graph.

The student will examine and categorize the extracted knowledge, and evaluate the knowledge by comparing them to external knowledge graphs.

The student should possess some working knowledge of neural networks, or be ready to learn substantial amount of new knowledge. Attention to detail is necessary.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

- Investigate new types of model prompts that can extract event knowledge from pretrained language models.

- Create methods that compare the extracted event knowledge against external event knowledge graphs or QA datasets.

(b) Development component
Supervisor A/P Li Boyang

272) Proj No. SCSE24-0279
Project Title Missing in a network: gapfilling with kriging
Project Summary Kriging is a classical geostatistical technique to obtain predictions at locations where measurements have not been taken, taking into account the spatial dependence in the phenomena of interest. For example, it is used to predict the level of infection of infectious diseases in regions where no data has been collected. These results can then be used to identify high risk areas and inform disease mitigation measures.

Geostatistical methods such as kriging often assume continuous, 2D space and model the relationship between measurements at different locations as depending on distance apart; however, in networks, geographical and Euclidean distance may not be the best representation of distance. To account for this in the context of water-levels along a river, a variation of kriging has been developed to gapfill time series of water-level measurements.

In this project, we want to investigate the use of this kriging-based gap-filling method in wider network settings. Since network models have been used in contexts ranging from telecommunications to finance, this is expected to have high practical relevance.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

To start, we will conduct a literature review on kriging and its variation for network gap-filling. For comparison purposes, we will also review network models and other methods used for gap-filling time series at nodes of a network.

(b) Development component

Using simulated data from network models and/or real-life case study data, we will implement different gap-filling approaches including the kriging-based method. To guide users towards the most appropriate choice, we will investigate their accuracy, tuning parameters and computational efficiency.
Supervisor Dr Michele Nguyen
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only
Type Research & Development
Keywords Data Analytics
Graph Theory

296) Proj No. SCSE24-0303
Project Title Exemplar selection for In-Context Learning under complex scenarios
Project Summary In-context learning has been widely adopted in large language models to solve complex tasks without the need to update model parameters. This is achieved by providing a few input-output examples as demonstrations to be fed as the prompt into the LLMs. Existing studies have revealed that selecting similar examples to the target is an optimal strategy. However, how this translates to more complicated tasks remains unclear. This project aims to study how to measure similarity in complicated tasks, such as natural language inference, information extraction, etc., and whether similarity is the optimal criteria. You will conduct empirical experiments to explore this research question.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
Explore how to measure similarity under complex scenarios and test whether similarity is the optimal metric to select good exemplars as prompt.


(b) Development component
Think critically why the metric works and how to improve the selection.
Supervisor Ast/P Wang Wenya
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only
Type Research & Development
Keywords Artificial Intelligence
Natural Language Processing/ Text Mining
297) Proj No. SCSE24-0304
Project Title Exemplar Selection for In-context learning under Out-Of-Domain Scenario
Project Summary In-context learning has been widely adopted in large language models to solve complex tasks without the need to update model parameters. This is achieved by providing a few input-output examples as demonstrations to be fed as the prompt into the LLMs. Existing studies have revealed that selecting similar examples to the target is an optimal strategy. However, how this translates to the out-of-domain (OOD) scenario remains unclear. When there is domain shift, it is not clear whether similarity is critical when selecting examples. This project aims to study how to measure similarity under the OOD setting and whether similarity is the optimal criteria. You will conduct empirical experiments to explore this research question.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
Explore what is the best metric under OOD setting.

(b) Development component
Think critically why certain metric is helpful.
Supervisor Ast/P Wang Wenya

Project Title Analyzing and Comparing LM architectures for Named Entity Recognition.
Project Summary This project delves into the realm of Natural Language Processing (NLP), specifically focusing on Language Model (LM) architectures and their efficacy in structured prediction such as NER. This study aims to investigate different LM architectures, such as encoder-only (BERT), encoder-decoder (T5) and decoder-only (GPT) architectures, when being used for learning an effective NER predictor. The evaluation will be centered on benchmark NER datasets. To obtain better performances, you need to tailor the design of different LM architectures towards sequence prediction, determine which configuration gives the best results. The outcome is a comprehensive analysis on how each LM architecture can better serve the task, and which gives the best performances.

300) Proj No. SCSE24-0307
Project Title Can Encoder-only Models become a Unified Reasoner?
Project Summary Generative language models which are based on the decoder architecture have been widely used to solve various tasks. Through a unified generative objective, these models can act as a general-purpose reasoner without the need to store multiple models when solving different tasks. On the other hand, the encoder-only models such as BERT are usually used separately for fine-tuning under different objectives. This project aims to explore whether the encoder-only models can also serve as a unified reasoner across different NLP tasks. This requires the student to explore a unified training objective to combine various tasks.

Specific details:
(a) Design component
Design a suitable objective to be used to train a unified encoder-only model.

(b) Implementation component

Project Title Effective Multimodal Sarcasm Detection
Project Summary Sarcasm detection is a challenging task which aims to identify opposite meanings between the author's true intent and that reflected from the surface form given. Considering this difficulty, multiple modalities are usually involved to aid sarcasm identification. For example, when proving both an image and a textual description, we can decide whether the image-text pair is sarcastic by examining possible contradictions or contrastiveness between the two modalities. In this project, you will explore effective strategies to identify sarcastic instances under the multimodal setting.

Specific details:
(a) Design component
Design effective frameworks to identify sarcastic instances with multiple modalities.

(b) Implementation component

Project Summary This project is a place-holder. Often students want to pursue their own ideas, but the student/supervisor allocation process for FYPs lack flexibility to do so. As such, I am proposing this "open-ended" project, subject to the restriction that it need to be data science related, so that a driven student with good ideas can use this as a way to pursue said ideas.

Note that the student's ideas will need to be developed in discussion with and vetted by me first, and we have to mutually agree first about the project agenda.

Student MUST first discuss with me their idea and get approval before bidding for this project. In the past, for similar project, students have bid without consultation and approval, leading to a rather unpleasant experience for both myself and the student.

Only students with very high academic ability should apply, since this project would naturally also expect the student to function reasonably independently.

As a final note: Student will need to learn and use Latex for preparing all documentation and project reports.

313) Proj No. SCSE24-0320
Project Title Deep Unfolding-Aided Hybrid-Field Channel Estimation for THz UM-MIMO Systems
Project Summary For effective Terahertz (THz) communications, it is essential to use densely packed antenna arrays to achieve significant beamforming gains. Ultra-massive multiple-input multiple-output (UM-MIMO) communications in the THz bands can achieve data rates up to several terabits per second (Tbps). Thus, THz UM-MIMO technology, utilizing an array-of-subarrays (AoSA) configuration, is considered a crucial component for enabling 6G networks. Nevertheless, the challenge of precise and efficient channel estimation, which is already a problem in massive MIMO systems at lower frequencies, becomes even more pronounced in THz UM-MIMO communications. Due to the increased array aperture and smaller wavelength, the region of near-field radiation extends, which means that the far-filed approximation becomes less practical for THz UM-MIMO systems. Therefore, the hybrid-field THz UM-MIMO channel model that blends both spherical and planar wavefronts is deemed a better alternative. This project envisions a deep unfolding (DU)-based approach to improve channel estimation in hybrid-field THz UM-MIMO networks, designed to be scalable to large-scale array configurations and to have low computational complexity. Specifically, it focuses on channel estimation during uplink transmissions, intending to reconstruct the THz channel based on the measurements of signals received after pilot signals are transmitted by the user equipment (UEs).

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
To successfully advance this proposal, the student should have knowledge or expertise in at least one of the following areas:
1. A solid foundation in machine learning (ML), especially in supervised learning.
2. Proficiency in programming and debugging in Python, complemented by experience in MATLAB.
3. An understanding of wireless communications, including Terahertz (THz) channels and multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO) systems.
(b) Development component
Develop algorithms for channel estimation during uplink transmissions based on the measurements of signals received after pilot signals are transmitted by the user equipment.
Supervisor A/P A S Madhukumar
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only
Type Research & Development
Keywords Machine Learning
Wireless and Mobile Networks
314) Proj No. SCSE24-0321
Project Title DRL-Powered Resource Coordination for UAV-THz Computation Offloading
Project Summary The necessity for adept data handling and computation is indispensable in the realm of the industrial Internet of Things (IIoT). However, the capabilities of IIoT could be notably restricted by the limited power and processing power of ground-based IIoT nodes. The advent of multi-access edge computing (MEC), which brings computing closer to the data source through edge access points (E-APs), emerges as an effective solution to enhance IIoT data processing needs. In particular, unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) with their adjustable flight paths stand out as promising enablers for advanced MEC services to IIoT nodes. Additionally, Terahertz (THz) communications with their vast bandwidth offer the potential for extremely high data transmission rates, supporting the swift offloading of computing tasks. This project proposes a UAV-supported MEC framework for IIoT networks, employing a UAV to provide computation offloading services to terrestrial IIoT user equipments (UEs). The goal is to refine overall computation offloading performance, e.g., minimizing delay, optimizing energy efficiency, and maximizing the amount of data processed, while meeting realistic limits including quality of service (QoS), UAV movement, energy availability, and computational capacity. To achieve this, a deep reinforcement learning (DRL)-based algorithm is expected to be developed, with scalability and manageable complexity.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
For the successful progression of this project, it is expected that the student will have expertise or a strong understanding in at least one of the following areas:
1. A solid grasp of machine learning (ML) concepts, especially deep reinforcement learning (DRL).
2. Strong programming and problem-solving skills in Python, and secondary familiarity with MATLAB.
3. A good understanding of wireless communication systems, particularly those involving Terahertz (THz) channels, UAV-mounted networks, and multi-access edge computing (MEC).
(b) Development component
Develop a deep reinforcement learning (DRL)-based algorithm with scalability and manageable complexity.
Supervisor A/P A S Madhukumar

315) Proj No. SCSE24-0322
Project Title A mixed THz/FSO system for 6G wireless communication: A Stochastic geometry-based analysis
Project Summary The millimeter frequencies have been introduced in 5G communications with the aim of providing high data rates. However, the upcoming 6G technology will push the frequency band to the terahertz range, which is between 0.1 THz and 10 THz, aiming to meet higher demands for bandwidth and data rates. In this regard, Terahertz (THz) communication assisted by free space optics (FSO) technology will be the new frontier for meeting the demands of next-generation wireless communications. The FSO and THz systems demonstrate different characteristics, with FSO communication being particularly affected by fog-induced attenuation, while THz communication is more vulnerable to signal degradation from rain and atmospheric molecular adsorptions. In such adverse weather conditions, a mixed THz/FSO system can be proposed to enhance the coverage and reliability, while delivering high data rates and extensive bandwidth. Further, the stochastic geometry-based approach can be used to investigate the performance of the proposed mixed THz/FSO.
The main objectives are:
1. To propose a mixed THz/FSO system for a backhaul wireless network.
2. To evaluate the performance of the proposed mixed THz/FSO system under fading, turbulence, pointing errors, and atmospheric pathloss attenuation.
3. To derive the various performance metrics: coverage probability, average SER, and ergodic capacity.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
Literature review: Conduct the state-of-the-art review in THz and FSO, as well as the latest advancements in 6G wireless communication, to identify potential areas of integration and performance enhancement techniques for THz and FSO.
(b) Development component
Simulation model: A simulation model for a mixed THz/FSO system based on stochastic geometry can be created using software like MATLAB or other suitable simulation tools.
Performance evaluation: The performance of the mixed THz/FSO system based on stochastic geometry can be analysed by deriving the expression for the performances metrices, such as coverage probability, average SER, and ergodic capacity.
Supervisor A/P A S Madhukumar
Joint Industry Project/
