Type Research & Development
Keywords Wireless and Mobile Networks
316) Proj No. SCSE24-0323
Project Title Multiple intelligent reflecting surfaces (IRS) assisted FSO system for 6G wireless communication: A performance analysis.
Project Summary Recently, free space optics (FSO) communication gained interest for its high bandwidth, enabling fast data transmission and license-free spectrum above 300 GHz. It is ideal for line-of-sight (LoS) communication, offering low interference and high security. Therefore, the FSO can be explored for backhaul networks for 6G wireless communication and explored as a last-mile option in rural areas. However, FSO faces challenges like atmospheric turbulence, fog, and pointing errors caused by environmental factors. On the other hand, the intelligent reflecting surfaces (IRS) or reconfigurable intelligence surfaces (RIS) has been gaining significant attention in the field of wireless communication systems. They have the potential to reduce obstacles, improve reliability, and create alternative routes for signal transmission. Therefore, the IRS-assisted FSO system can be emerged a potential solution for the wireless backhaul networks. Hence, the objective of this project is to examine the performance of multiple IRS-assisted FSO system for backhaul scenarios. The results of this project will offer valuable understanding regarding the benefits of IRS technology for FSO communication and how it influences the performance of 6G wireless communication systems.
The main objectives of this project are:
1. To propose a multiple IRS-assisted FSO system with an arbitrary number of reflecting elements
2. To investigate the performance of the proposed multiple IRS-assisted FSO system by considering factors such as turbulence, pointing errors, and weather-related signal attenuation.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
Literature review: Conduct an extensive review of IRS and FSO technologies, 6G wireless communication standards, and research papers to understand the current state of IRS and FSO technologies, as well as potential use cases that could benefit from their integration.
(b) Development componentSimulation model: The simulation model for multiple IRS-assisted FSO system can be developed, utilizing software such as MATLAB or other appropriate simulation tools.
Performance evaluation:
The performance of the proposed multiple IRS assisted FSO system can be investigated in terms of various performance metrics such as outage probability, average SER, and ergodic capacity.
Supervisor A/P A S Madhukumar

317) Proj No. SCSE24-0324
Project Title A RIS-assisted hybrid FSO/THz system for next-generation backhaul network: A stochastic geometry-based analysis
Project Summary Reconfigurable Intelligent Surfaces (RIS) have garnered considerable interest in wireless communication systems. They offer the potential to mitigate obstacles, enhance reliability, and establish alternative paths for signal transmission. On the other hand, Terahertz (THz) and free space optics (FSO) technologies, operating near THz frequency range, will be the new frontier for meeting the high data-rate and huge bandwidth requirements of next-generation wireless communications. While FSO and THz systems possess distinct attributes, FSO communication faces challenges such as fog-induced attenuation, whereas THz communication is susceptible to signal degradation from rain and atmospheric molecular adsorptions. To address these issues in adverse weather conditions, a hybrid FSO/THz system can be proposed, enhancing coverage and reliability while maintaining high data rates and expansive bandwidth. Additionally, employing a stochastic geometry-based approach can help to analyse the performance of such hybrid FSO/THz systems.
The main objectives of this project are:
1. To propose a RIS-assisted hybrid FSO/THz system for a backhaul wireless network.
2. To evaluate the performance of the proposed RIS-assisted hybrid FSO/THz system using stochastic geometry approach.
3. To derive the various performance metrics: coverage probability, average SER, and ergodic capacity.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
Literature review: Conduct the state-of-the-art review in THz and FSO, as well as the different switching techniques for hybrid FSO/THz system. Identify potential areas of integration and performance enhancement techniques for THz and FSO systems, paving the way for future advancements in wireless communication networks.
(b) Development component
Simulation model: A simulation model for a RIS-assisted hybrid FSO/THz system using stochastic geometry approach can be developed using software such as MATLAB or other appropriate simulation tools.
Performance evaluation: Investigate the performance of the proposed RIS-aided hybrid FSO/THz system by deriving the expression for the performances metrices, including coverage probability, average SER, and ergodic capacity.
Supervisor A/P A S Madhukumar

318) Proj No. SCSE24-0325
Project Title AI-Based Edge Caching for 5G-and-Beyond Industrial IoT Networks
Project Summary Enabling wireless communications for industrial Internet-of-Things (IIoT) use cases with strict reliability and latency requirements is an open research challenge due to the harsh indoor and outdoor wireless environments in industrial factories.

To enable timely access for IIoT services, popular content statistics based on the underlying IIoT network traffic are collected. Thereafter, artificial intelligence (AI) based methods are employed to predict popular files that are likely to be requested by end users in IIoT networks. Collectively, such an approach is also known as edge caching, and it is one of the research areas gaining interest for fifth generation (5G)-and-beyond IIoT networks.

Therefore, this project investigates the applications of AI-based edge caching and 5G communications as promising technologies to support ultra-reliable low-latency content access in 5G-and-beyond IIoT networks.

Specifically, an AI-based edge caching strategy is investigated for 5G-and-beyond IIoT networks. Using non-learning based least frequently used (LFU) and least recently used (LRU) algorithms as benchmarks, edge caching strategies are evaluated based on cache hit rate, latency, and energy efficiency using realistic network traffic models.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
Literature review of IIoT networks and edge caching strategies
Investigate AI-based techniques for popular content prediction for IIoT use cases.

(b) Development component
Build suitable AI model variants, and fine tune for the proposed application.
Train and test with simulated data.
Test the proposed solution with real measurement data from a testbed in ARTC, A*STAR.
Supervisor A/P A S Madhukumar
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Hardware & Software (Mostly Software)
Type Research & Development
Keywords Artificial Intelligence
Machine Learning

Project Title Towards 5G Industrial Adoption: Digital Twin for Wireless Performance Evaluation
Project Summary Performance degradation in wireless communications within industrial Internet-of-Things (IIoT) networks can occur due to the harsh conditions of the IIoT environment, in settings such as a refinery or a highly attenuated indoor environment due to signal blockages and/or interferences. As a result, the feasibility of deploying 5G for specific IIoT use cases currently remains challenging to ascertain due to limited approaches to do so.
This project looks into developing a digital twin for 5G-enabled IIoT networks and produce a wireless performance analysis for IIoT use cases through emulation.

(b) Implementation component

Project Title Deep Learning-Based Quality of Experience (QoE) Classification for Optimal Resource Allocation in Manufacturing Networks
Project Summary In today's interconnected manufacturing systems, the efficient allocation of resources and reliable communication is of paramount importance. To address this challenge, this research project focuses on developing a deep learning-based Quality of Experience (QoE) classification system. The objective is to accurately assess and classify the perceived quality of different manufacturing network services of levels into application types. Manufacturing network services to be studied include robot operations, video streaming, and real-time analytics.

Moreover, this project looks into combining deep learning techniques into the classification technique to automatically extract relevant features from data, to be able to handle large datasets and model complex patterns of manufacturing network traffic.

Project Title Automated Testing of Cross-Language Communications in RPC Frameworks - Part1
Project Summary Remote Procedure Call (RPC) is a software communication protocol that one program can use to request a service from a program located in another computer on a network without having to understand the network's details. RPC uses the client-server model. The requesting program is a client, and the service-providing program is the server. The client and server may use different programming languages. Popular open-source RPC frameworks include gRPC and Apache Thrift. In this project, we build on a systematic automated testing platform in order to discover potential implementation bugs in these frameworks, specifically for cross-language communications.

Specific details:
(a) Design component

Design templates for effective test generation.

(b) Implementation component

Extend testing platform to handle different programming languages for both RPC client and server.

342) Proj No. SCSE24-0349
Project Title Efficient generation of radiance fields for 3D scenes
Project Summary Reconstructing 3D scenes to support high quality new view synthesis is an important task for computer vision and graphics applications in various real world scenarios. In 2019, a neural representation called NeRF was developed, which models a scene as a radiance field and shows great success in photo-realistic rendering of scenes with complex geometry and view-dependent appearance. This representation was then quickly extended in different ways and applied in generative models, appearance acquisition, surface reconstruction, appearance editing, etc. While the original NeRF is based on MLP and requires small memory, it takea a long time to train. Many improvements have been proposed. In this project, we will examine two of such improvements that leverage a voxel grid of features in radiance field modeling [1,2]. The main tasks of the project include:

1) test and evaluate the algorithms proposed in [1,2].
2) propose and implement some further improvement.


References:

[1]. Alex Yu, Ruilong Li, Matthew Tancik, Hao Li, Ren Ng, Angjoo Kanazawa: "PlenOctrees for Real-time Rendering of Neural Radiance Fields". ICCV 2021: 5732-5741
[2]. Sara Fridovich-Keil, Alex Yu, Matthew Tancik, Qinhong Chen, Benjamin Recht, Angjoo Kanazawa: "Plenoxels: Radiance Fields without Neural Networks". CVPR 2022: 5491-5500

Specific details:
Implement and evaluate PlenOctrees & Penoxels

Project Title Fine-tuning stable diffusion on fashion
Project Summary Diffusion models [1] are popular deep generative models for text-to-image synthesis. This project aims to fine-tune a diffuse model on a fashion dataset [2] to generate fashion images from a text prompt. The basic idea is to leverage the semantic prior embedded in the pretrained latent stable diffusion model. The fine-tuning is implemented using the low-rank adaptation technique (LoRA) [3,4]. The scope of the project includes implementation, testing and exploration for further improvement.

Project Title Graph CNN for 3D meshes
Project Summary MeshCNN is a convolutional neural network with an edge, which was developed for analyzing triangular mesh models and published in 2019 in ACM Transactions on Graphics. Triangular meshes provide an efficient representation for 3D shapes and have gained wide applications in computer games, animation, AR/VR, etc. MeshCNN generalizes classic CNNs to triangular meshes by leveraging the intrinsic features of triangular meshes and designing specialized convolution and pooling layers that operate on the mesh edges, and provides a powerful plug-and-play framework for various tasks.

This project aims to evaluate MeshCNN's performance in different aspects and explore general graph CNN for 3D triangular meshes.

Implement MeshCNN and explore its generalization

350) Proj No. SCSE24-0357
Project Title Information Extraction from PubMed Literatures for Pathogen Database Creation
Project Summary This project aims to create a PubMed Pathogen Database from extracting related information from PubMed literatures. It mainly consists of two main processes, namely automated web scraping and information extraction.
The automated web scraping process involves downloading both the contents of scientific articles and its corresponding metadata at scheduled intervals (e.g., weekly, bi-weekly, monthly, etc.). Then, the relevant scientific articles which contain information on related pathogen of interest (e.g., E. Coli, Salmonella, and Campylobacter) are filtered. The semi-structured texts from the articles (e.g., abstract, main body, tables, etc.) and structured texts from the metadata are extracted as “raw” data for processing. This information extraction process involves two aspects. First, the extraction of assay information from the textual contents of the scientific literature. This involves extracting specific terms for a set of specialized microbiology categories (i.e., MLST, MIC (in SIR), Plasmid, Resistance Genes, SPI, Virulence Genes, and SNP info), from the semi-structured contents including free-formed texts (sentences), and tables. Second, the extraction of supplementary information from the corresponding meta-data (i.e., Isolate ID, Isolation date, Host, Geographical location, Latitude, Longitude, Taxonomy, Genus, Serovar, Subspecies, Host Healthy State, Bio-project, Sample Accession, Run Accession, PubMed ID and Organization Name).

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
Advance AI techniques such as Large Language Models (LLMs) or Pre-trained Language Models PLMs) for the information extraction will be investigated to acquire the attributes from the scientific literature to construct the pathogen profiles. Moreover, certain information (attributes) may not be provided by the NCBI database in the meta-data (e.g., Latitude and Longitude). So techniques are needed for the automated extraction.

(b) Development component
The development will be done according to the implementation of the two processes. Python is used for the development work.
Supervisor A/P Hui Siu Cheung
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only
Type Research & Development
Keywords Artificial Intelligence
Bioinformatics
Natural Language Processing/ Text Mining

Project Summary Cybersecurity Event Extraction, which aims to automatically obtain structured security information from cybersecurity news texts, has attracted increasing interest from both academia and industry. Leveraging on current deep learning Natural Language Processing (NLP) techniques, cybersecurity event extraction systems can significantly reduce human efforts in gathering security information and provide insights for cybersecurity professionals to analyse and address security risks and vulnerabilities. In this project, we investigate deep learning models for Event Extraction from cybersecurity news articles, including detection and categorization of event instances (such as malware attack, phishing, etc.).

Specific details:

353) Proj No. SCSE24-0360
Project Title TTP Identification from Unstructured Text
Project Summary Understanding TTP (tactics, techniques, and procedures) patterns is crucial as it provides insights into the methods that adversaries have employed to achieve their objectives. Notably, TTP techniques exhibit a certain degree of consistency across different adversaries and remain the same over time. Analyzing TTP patterns can help identify the long-term behavior and essential characteristics of attackers. As such, defenders can improve their defense against potential future cyber-attacks. Currently, there is no publicly available benchmark dataset for training TTP classification from the CTI (cyber threat intelligence) reports. Constructing such a corpus is challenging as each CTI report may be associated with multiple tactics, techniques, and procedures. In this project, we aim to go beyond extraction of techniques/sub-techniques used and extend it into the specifics of how the actor executed each tactic or technique as well as the associated codes/files employed and the sequence of execution. This comprehensive approach provides a detailed and holistic understanding of adversary techniques to empower cybersecurity professionals in anticipating and proactively defending against advanced and evolving cyber threats. For TTPs identification, we will analyse and select an appropriate dataset that aligns with our objectives. The MITRE ATT&CK framework, created by MITRE in 2018, is a model that breaks down cyber-attacks into tactics, techniques, and procedures.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
Coupled with the predefined knowledge resources, Natural Language Processing (NLP) methods can be used for effectively mapping CTI reports to the pertinent TTPs. Building a deep learning model to identify the TTP name and elements requires domain experts to annotate the training corpus.

(b) Development component
The student will develop techniques for TTP identification and evaluate the performance of the proposed techniques.
Supervisor A/P Hui Siu Cheung
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only
Type Research & Development
Keywords Natural Language Processing/ Text Mining
Machine Learning

355) Proj No. SCSE24-0362
Project Title Event Detection for Biomedical Text
Project Summary In the last decade, text mining in biomedical domain has received significant attention in research and many studies have been devoted to advancing the state-of-the-art natural language processing (NLP) techniques to biomedical text. Event detection is the primary step in the event extraction task, whose objective is to detect events via trigger mentions that signify the occurrence of events with a particular type. Essentially, event detection requires the construction of a semantic relationship between input text representations and the set of predefined event type labels. However, existing methods tend to pay most attention to learn the input text representations and simply use one-hot vectors for event type
labels. In this project, we investigate advance AI techniques such as LLMs and PLMs for biomedical event detection.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
AI techniques such as Large Language Models (LLMs) and Pre-trained Language Models (PLMs) will be investigated.

(b) Development component
The project will develop AI techniques for biomedical event detection. The student will conduct experiments based on the benchmark GENIA Event 2011 (GE11) dataset. for performance evaluation.

Project Title Music from the air - digital theremin
Project Summary This project requires that the student MUST BE FAMILIAR with the theory of music (scales, cords, harmony, etc) and can play some musical instrument.
Theremin is an electronic musical instrument controlled without physical contact by hands of the performer. It was invented in the 1919. Theremin consists of two metal antennas that sense the relative position of the thereminist's hands and control pitch of the notes with one hand, and volume with the other. The instrument can be tuned to each individual player including the range of the notes and volumes to be produced.
This project requires that the student MUST BE FAMILIAR with the theory of music (scales, cords, harmony, etc) and can play some musical instrument. 358) Proj No. SCSE24-0365
Project Title Music from the air - digital terpsiton
Project Summary One hundred years ago the theremin was invented. This is an electronic musical instrument controlled without physical contact by hands of the performer. The theremin consists of two metal antennas that sense the relative position of the thereminist's hands and control pitch of the notes with one hand, and volume with the other. Later the inventor, Leo Theremin, proposed another musical instrument -- terpsitone -- named after the Greek Goddess of dance Terpsihore. The idea was that sound can be generated by sensing the body of dancer. It was proposed to be made on the same tracking principles as the theremin except that it was designed as a platform on which the dancer had to move/dance. This instrument however never was really made except a few test copies due to the complexity of tracking and using.
This project requires that the student MUST BE FAMILIAR with the theory of music (scales, cords, harmony, etc) and can play some musical instrument. The student will conduct a feasibility study on the hypothesis that the Kinect can be used for making any reasonable musical sounds while tracing the body of the player. Unity 3D system will be used for p[rogramming. The project will also require to make user study hence the student will need to have to approach about 20 other students willing to participate in it. The purpose of the user study is to tests the developed software and obtain the user feedback. Students with and without knowledge of playing musical instruments will be needed. The project can be also done on the student's computer provided it is able to work with Microsoft Kinect 2nd generation (requires USB 3).

Reference:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gH0Y5M46Gqc&list=PLbKLI6FekIW4D-hV9pOyc0kS3ZTIIhttI&index=39

Specific details:
(a) Design component

(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
To explore whether Kinect can be realistically used for making music while tracking the body of the player

(b) Development component
To make a pilot version of the application

Project Title Virtual assembling using hand tracking with Leap Motion controller
Project Summary In this project the student will design and develop virtual assembling in Unity 3D system using hand tracking by Leap Motion controller.

First, the student will learn how Leap Motion controller can track hands and will understand how well it can be used for simulating virtual assembling operations where objects have to be picked up, positioned and placed by one or two hands.
Next, the student will learn how Leap Motion controller can be used together with Unity3D system.
Next, the student will need to design the user interaction based on the study performed. The interaction should reliably simulate real-life assembling operations which are performed by hands on top of table. The interaction has to be performed using the help of Unity 3D physics engine which computes collision detection of the virtual fingers with the objects. However, the student will need to design and implement measures compensating for luck of physical feedback forces which can be felt by the user.
Finally, a user study has to be done to verify whether virtual interaction is as good as real-life interaction when performing assembling operations.

The project can be performed on home PC/notebook.

Requirements: programming using C/C++.
Refer to http://unity3d.com

Specific details:
To design and implement hand gestures and the virtual scene for the user testing.

363) Proj No. SCSE24-0371
Project Title Network Embedding for Drug Target Discovery in Cancer Signaling Network: A Machine Learning-based Approach
Project Summary The goal of target combination prediction in signaling networks is to predict target (nodes) combinations that can effectively modulate a set of disease nodes in order to achieve a specifi c therapeutic goal (e.g., reducing the activity of ERKPP protein by 50%). An in silico solution to this problem can aid in early rejection of unsuitable targets and guide the design of further in vitro and in vivo drug combination experiments, thereby reducing the cost and time for drug development. An effective solution needs to analyze the topology of the neighborhood of diseases nodes along with their disease-specifi c roles in order to capture crosstalks between pathways and their impact on targets. In this project, the candidate has to explore how network embedding can facilitate this. To this end, he/she will built on top of a state-of-the-art attributed network embedding technique that has been recently proposed by our group.

Specific details:

(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

364) Proj No. SCSE24-0372
Project Title License plate detection 1
Project Summary License plate detection is widely employed in parking organisation systems, traffic control administration, and vehicle tracking. License plate recognition consists of two main mechanisms: license plate detection (LPD) and the subsequent license plate identification (LPI). Algorithms adopted for LPD can select a candidate region as a license plate according to defined conditions or properties. However, the candidate region may not be a license plate. Hence, LPD is combined with LPI. The region containing a license plate can be described by several properties, such as a specific colour, and includes a rich set of vertical edges or characters. However, another region within the image can also have similar properties. In this project, we will study how license plate detection can be done in the presence of confounding factors as described above. The method could use either deep learning or non-deep learning methods.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
Read paper on license plate detection
Analyse described algorithm and suggest improvements.

(b) Development component
Implement the code for license plate recognition on publicly available benchmark datasets. Implementation can be in Python or other preferable language.
Supervisor A/P Deepu Rajan
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only
Type Research & Development
Keywords Image Analysis & Processing

378) Proj No. SCSE24-0386
Project Title Explainable AI to uncover significant brain structure-function coupling changes in humans with autism spectrum disorder (ASD)
Project Summary Structural and functional connectivity changes are observed in individuals with autism spectrum disorder (ASD). Diffusion-weighted imaging has revealed structural changes in tracts, including the inferior parietal, occipitoparietal, inferior frontal, and inferior temporal cortex in patients with ASD. Resting-state functional MRI (rsfMRI) studies have identified alterations in functional connectivity between various brain regions, such as inferior parietal, superior frontal and cingulate regions in patients with ASD. Previous studies have implied that alterations in structural–functional connectivity (SC–FC) coupling are also associated with ASD. It would be interesting to explain the significant SC–FC coupling changes across the entire brain in individuals with ASD.

Since both SC and FC can be represented as graphs with brain regions as nodes connected by edges, Graph Convolution Networks (GCN) are powerful for building an ASD patient classification model while learning the SC-FC coupling strengths. Several explainable AI techniques, such as GNNexplainer and PG explainer, can provide post-hoc explanations of the GNN model, revealing important edges and nodes. In this project, we aim to classify patients with ASD and normal controls while learning SC-FC coupling strength based on the GCN model. Furthermore, we intend to reveal important SC-FC coupling information for ASD based on explainable AI. The Autism Brain Imaging Data Exchange II will be the main dataset used for the experiments.

Throughout this project, the student will gain familiarity with deep learning frameworks, particularly PyTorch Geometric, and its explain library. Additionally, the student will develop an in-depth understanding of the GCN mechanism, as well as explainable AI techniques.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
Student will research on how functional MRI is used to study brain diseases

(b) Development component
The necessary routines will be developed in Python and Pytorch.
Supervisor Prof Jagath Chandana Rajapakse

379) Proj No. SCSE24-0387
Project Title Predicting multiple cognition functions simultaneously from brain functional connectivity via interpretable multi-task learning network
Project Summary Resting-state functional magnetic resonance imaging (rs-fMRI) has been widely used to understand the functional organization of the brain, characterized by the functional connectivity between brain regions via the synchronization of their fMRI signals. Utilizing machine learning techniques, this functional connectivity can robustly predict single cognitive functions, such as fluid intelligence, sustained attention, working memory, and creative ability. Cognitive functions, like fluid intelligence and crystallized intelligence, are known to be highly correlated and, to some extent, share common neural mechanisms. Therefore, it would be interesting to simultaneously predict multiple cognitive functions, and explore both distinct and common brain functional features of multiple cognitive functions, potentially enhancing the prediction power.

Several deep learning models have been applied to brain functional connectivity for the prediction of single cognitive function, including BrainNetCNN and models based on Graph convolutional network. Additionally, various explainable techniques, such as attention methods and post-hoc method (e.g., IG, GNNexplainer), can be adopted to open the ‘black box’ and explain the learning features. In this project, we aim to design an interpretable multi-task deep learning network that performed on brain functional connectivity to predict multiple cognitive functions simultaneously. Furthermore, we aim to explain the important common functional features contributing to the prediction of all cognitive functions and distinct brain functional features contributing to single cognitive function. The Human Connectome Project S1200 dataset will be the main dataset used for the experiments.

Throughout this project, the student will gain familiarity with deep learning frameworks such as PyTorch. Also, the student will develop an in-depth understanding of the attention mechanism, as well as multi-task learning for deep learning.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
Student will research how functional MRI is used to study cognitive function

(b) Development component
Student will develop necessary routines in Python and Pytorch
Supervisor Prof Jagath Chandana Rajapakse

Project Title Comparison of U-net architectures for segmentation of subcortical structures of the brain
Project Summary Subcortical structures are small structures in the brain and perform important functions. For example, thalamus can be considered the grand central station of the brain – most of the incoming sensory information passes through the thalamus enroute to the cortex. Abnormalities of the subcortical structures have been observed in patients with schizophrenia, Parkinson’s disease, Alzheimer’s disease, etc. Therefore, automatic segmentation of subcortical structures and evaluation of their volumes have a variety of applications including diagnosis of brain diseases.

U-net are powerful deep neural network architectures for medical image segmentation. Recently, several enhancements to U-net architectures have been proposed, for example, introducing attention mechanism, transformers, etc. In this project, we investigate recent U-net architectures such as attention UNet, Swin UNet, ThansUnet, etc. for segmentation of subcortical structures.

The student will develop algorithms by using Python and Pytorch/Tensorflow libraries.

Project Title Federated learning for disease classification from functional MRI data
Project Summary Federated learning (FL) is a machine learning setting where many clients (e.g. mobile devices or whole organizations) collaboratively train a model under the orchestration of a central server (e.g. service provider), while keeping the training data decentralized. Similarly, federated analytics allows data scientists to generate analytical insight from the combined information in distributed datasets without requiring data centralization.

Resting-state functional MRI (rs-fMRI) has been able to detect a variety of brain diseases. However, fMRI datasets gathered in one site are usually very small and so our aim is to make use of fMRI datasets gathered on different sites. In this project, we will use FL to learn rs-fMRI data gathered at different sites predict brain disease such as ADHD and Autism Spectrum Disorders.

The student will develop algorithms by using Python and Pytorch/Tensorflow libraries.

Project Title U-net for segmentation of brain lesions from CT head scans

Project Title Lightweight deep learning (1)
Project Summary Deep learning architectures typically contains tens of millions of parameters making it difficult to deploy them on mobile devices. Lightweight deep learning architectures contain several times less number of parameters. Although the number of floating point operations for inference reduces considerably, there is a trade off due to loss in accuracy for a particular task. In this project, we sill study the EfficientNet light weight architecture and implement it for computer vision tasks. A research component of the project comprises suggesting alternative architectures that can improve accuracy and possibly reduce the number of parameters.

416) Proj No. SCSE24-0429
Project Title The dynamic graph learning based on the spiking neural network
Project Summary Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) have recently become increasingly popular due to their ability to learn complex systems of relations or interactions. Despite the plethora of different models for deep learning on graphs, few approaches have been proposed for dealing with graphs that are dynamic in nature (e.g. evolving features or connectivity over time).

Spiking neural networks (SNNs) are the third-generation neural networks. Unlike conventional neural networks, SNNs transmit information via the precise timing (temporal) of spike trains consisting of a series of spikes (discrete), rather than a real value (continuous). Driven by the sparse nature of spike events and event-driven computation, SNNs offer exceptional power efficiency and are the preferred neural networks in neuromorphic architectures. Despite their excellent potential, SNNs have been limited to relatively simple tasks (e.g., image classification) and small datasets (e.g., MNIST and CIFAR), on a rather shallow structure.

This project targets the probability of incorporating the SNNs into dynamic graph learning. On the one hand, this combination can help model the temporal data in graph use SNNs manner. On the other hand, it can also help reduce the energy consumption of graph learning.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

The research component includes the basic GNN reference or prediction, the representation learning on dynamic graph, and the SNNs structure.

The development component includes a detailed combination of dynamic GNN and SNNs. Moreover, the design should keep a low energy consumption with a state-of-the-art accuracy.
Supervisor Ast/P Luo Siqiang
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only
Type Research & Development
Keywords Machine Learning
Data Mining
417) Proj No. SCSE24-0430
Project Title Subgraph Extraction Algorithm for Large Scale Heterogeneous Graph
Project Summary Large-scale heterogeneous graphs, containing different types of nodes and edges, bring new challenges to the efficiency and scalability of graph representation learning and Graph Neural Network-based algorithms. For some graph learning tasks, such as inductive graph reasoning, pre-training on whole graph data suffers from serious computational costs. Therefore, This project aims to propose an efficient subgraph extraction algorithm for large-scale heterogeneous graphs. The extracted subgraph contains a limited number of representative nodes and selected edge types, which can reflect the topological characteristics of the entire graph and is expected to be applied to various graph neural network models.

420) Proj No. SCSE24-0433
Project Title Smart Contract Vulnerability Repair Based on Large Language Model
Project Summary Smart contracts have emerged as revolutionary tools in the blockchain domain, enabling automated, trustless transactions over decentralized networks. However, the dynamic nature of these contracts often makes them susceptible to vulnerabilities, which can have severe financial and trust implications. This research presents a unique methodology that synergizes the capabilities of large language models (LLMs) with traditional static and dynamic analysis technologies to promote the repair of smart contract vulnerabilities. Our approach delves into the root causes of these vulnerabilities by leveraging the analytical prowess of LLMs like GPT-4. The LLMs dissect and interpret the inherent logic and structure of smart contracts, pinpointing potential weaknesses. These identified vulnerabilities are then further scrutinized using traditional static analysis for code anomalies and dynamic analysis for runtime behavior deviations. This multi-faceted approach ensures a thorough evaluation of the smart contract's safety.

Project Title Scenario generation methods for functional safety testing of automated driving systems
Project Summary Scenario-based methods are both essential and effective when evaluating the functional safety of automated driving systems (ADSs). With the help of high-fidelity 3D simulators, almost all scenario types, e.g., normal urban driving, traffic jams, or extreme situations, can be constructed and simulated. However, with great flexibility comes infinitely large scenario search space. How to effectively search for relevant scenarios towards high diversity coverage and low redundancy has been a hot research topic in academia.

In this project, we aim to apply and evaluate the performance of existing state-of-the-art (SOTA) scenario-based functional safety testing methods in Desay’s context, identify the limitations of the existing techniques concerning Desay’s requirements, and propose new efficient ways to generate critical scenarios.

Project Title Finding Instrumentable Locations for Fuzzing via Static Binary Analysis

432) Proj No. SCSE24-0445
Project Title Adversarial Training with Self-Supervised Learnable Attack Strategy
Project Summary Adversarial training (AT) has been demonstrated to be one of most effective methods to improve the model robustness against adversarail examples. AT methods inject adversarial examples (AEs) into the training procedure to improve the model robustness. The core element of the effectiveness of adversarial training is the generation of AEs. Most previous AT methods manually specify attack parameters to perform adversarial attacks for the AEs generation.We can regard a combination of the attack parameters of the adversarial attacks as an adversarial attack strategy. A series of related works have discovered that AEs generated by only one fixed adversarial attack strategy could limit the model robustness and they propose to adopt different adversarial attack strategies to generate AEs in the different training stages to improve the model robustness. However, these multi-stage attack strategies AT methods are also hand-crafted and require much prior-guided domain expertise, result in limited model robustness improvement. In this project, we will introduce the concept of “self-supervised learnable attack strategy” and propose a novel AT framework, dubbed LAS-AT. On the one hand, the proposed framework can generate adversarial attack strategies to improve the model robustness automatically. On the other hand, it enforces the model to predict the adversarial attack strategies to further improve the model robustness. Our framework is consist of a strategy network and a target network. The former controls the generation of AEs by producing the adversarial attack strategies. The later makes use of the generated AEs to improve his own model robustness. Moreover, the target network is enforced to predict the adversarial attack strategies to enhance the sensitivity to the attack strategies.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component


(b) Development component
Supervisor Prof Liu Yang
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only
Type Research & Development
Keywords Artificial Intelligence
Cyber Security

Project Title Generate Vulnerable Transaction Sequences for Smart Contract using Large Language Models

Subsequently, we can employ automated testing technology to evaluate smart contracts using these templates, significantly enhancing the efficiency of vulnerability exploiting.

435) Proj No. SCSE24-0448
Project Title Radio-Frequency (RF) Sensing for Deep Awareness of Human Physical Status - Part III
Project Summary Human physical status is a rather broad concept; it includes, among others, behaviors (e.g., laughing and crying), vital signs (e.g., respiration and heart beat), as well as gestures and gaits. Conventionally, being aware of all these aspects require a very diversified types of sensors, for example, electrocardiogram (ECG) for heat beat measurements and video analysis for gait recognition.

Recently, there is a trend of unifying all these sensing task into a single sensor based on Radio-Frequency (RF, e.g., WiFi), driven by the last development of signal processing and deep learning techniques. In particular, special type of RF sensors are developed main for such integrated tasks, which will be used by our project.

In this project, we intend to explore these newly available RF sensors. Essentially, we first need to gather a large amount of sensing data on human physical status, ranging from gesture/behavior to vital signs. Then we develop deep learning modules and train them to recognize various human physical statuses out of seemingly wild RF signals. If time allows and if we get a big team on this project, we could also extend the objective to sentimental analysis based on RF sensing.

In this project, you are supposed to use the most up-to-date RF sensors: we collect sensing data first and then we apply standard deep data analytics upon these data. So you are required to understand the basic concept of RF, and some basic knowledge of machine learning/data analytics would be a plus. For different parts of this project, we will focus on different human physical statuses. The exact target will be tailored to your interests.

Specific details:
(a) Design component

RF sensing module, and data analytics algorithms to process the raw GPS data.

(b) Implementation component

Implement the aforementioned designs

(a) Research component


(b) Development component
Supervisor A/P Luo Jun

Conventionally, being aware of all these aspects require a very diversified types of sensors, for example, electrocardiogram (ECG) for heat beat measurements and video analysis for gait recognition.

Recently, there is a trend of unifying all these sensing task into a single sensor based on Radio-Frequency (RF, e.g., WiFi), driven by the last development of signal processing and deep learning techniques. In particular, special type of RF sensors are developed main for such integrated tasks, which will be used by our project.

In this project, we intend to explore these newly available RF sensors. Essentially, we first need to gather a large amount of sensing data on human physical status, ranging from gesture/behavior to vital signs. Then we develop deep learning modules and train them to recognize various human physical statuses out of seemingly wild RF signals. If time allows and if we get a big team on this project, we could also extend the objective to sentimental analysis based on RF sensing.

In this project, you are supposed to use the most up-to-date RF sensors: we collect sensing data first and then we apply standard deep data analytics upon these data. So you are required to understand the basic concept of RF, and some basic knowledge of machine learning/data analytics would be a plus. For different parts of this project, we will focus on different human physical statuses. The exact target will be tailored to your interests.

Specific details:
(a) Design component

RF sensing module, and data analytics algorithms to process the raw GPS data.

(b) Implementation component

Implement the aforementioned designs

(a) Research component


(b) Development component

441) Proj No. SCSE24-0454
Project Title Radio-Frequency (RF) Sensing for Deep Awareness of Human Physical Status - Part VII
Project Summary While both outdoor and indoor localization methods are flourishing, how to properly marry them to offer pervasive localizability in urban areas remains open. Recently proposals on indoor-outdoor detection make the first step towards such an integration, yet complicated urban environments render such a binary classification incompetent.

Fortunately, the latest developments in Android have granted us access to raw GNSS measurements, which contain far more information than commonly derived GPS location indicators. Although this ability is limited to several up-to-date smartphones, we believe it will be adopted as a standard in the future.

In this project, we intend to explore these newly available measurements in order to better characterize the diversified urban environments. Essentially, we first need to gather a large amount of such raw GPS measurements, from various environments in our city, ranging from indoor to semi-indoor/outdoor, and further to pure outdoor. Then we tackle the challenges introduced by the complex GNSS data by applying a deep learning model to identify representations for respective location contexts. If time allows and if we get a big team on this project, we could also extend the objective to enabling the integration of a pervasive localization service

In this project, you are supposed to use Android smartphones or other smartwears (e.g., Smartwatch) to collect raw GPS readings, and then we apply standard deep data analytics upon these data. So you are required to understand Android, and some basic knowledge of machine learning/data analytics would be a plus. For Part III of this project, we mostly focus on semi-outdoor and pure outdoor data.

Specific details:
(a) Design component

Android GPS module, and data analytics algorithms to process the raw GPS data.

(b) Implementation component

Implement the aforementioned designs

(a) Research component


(b) Development component

442) Proj No. SCSE24-0455
Project Title Advanced U-net Architectures for Subcortical Structure Segmentation in Brain MRIs
Project Summary Background: Subcortical structures in the human brain, such as the thalamus, are critical for various functions, acting as key relay points for sensory information. Abnormalities in these structures are associated with numerous neurological disorders, including schizophrenia, Parkinson's disease, and Alzheimer's disease. Given their significance, precise segmentation and volume assessment of these structures are crucial for diagnosing and understanding these diseases.

Objective: This project aims to explore and refine advanced neural network architectures, specifically enhanced versions of U-net, for the automatic segmentation of subcortical brain structures. By leveraging recent innovations such as attention mechanisms and transformers, we seek to improve segmentation accuracy and efficiency, which could revolutionize diagnostic approaches for brain diseases.

Methodology: The project will involve:

· A comprehensive review of recent advancements in U-net architectures, including Attention U-net, Swin U-net, and TransU-net.

· Development and implementation of selected architectures using Python, with PyTorch as the primary deep learning libraries.

· Evaluation of the models on publicly available MRI datasets, focusing on segmentation accuracy, computational efficiency, and the ability to generalize across different datasets.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
The student will research on image segmentation methods and on brain subcortical structure segmentation

(b) Development component
The student will develop routines in Python and Pytorch/Tensorflow environment

449) Proj No. SCSE24-0462
Project Title Cluster Analysis on Dynamic Graphs
Project Summary Graph data is ubiquitous in real life. Examples include social networks, biological networks, transportation networks, communication networks, etc. Graph clustering aims to group vertices in a given graph such that vertices in the same cluster are densely connected, while vertices in different clusters are sparsely connected.

This project is to study the clustering problem on dynamic graphs that evolve/change over time. Dynamic graph clustering has many practical applications. For example, it can be used in online social networking sites for capturing users’ dynamic behaviours and performing dynamic service/apps recommendations.

Specially, the student is required to (1) collect real dynamic graphs, (2) design and implement an algorithm that is able to find clusters on dynamic graphs, (3) design and implement an algorithm that is able to trace how clusters evolve over time, and (4) evaluate the two algorithms on real dynamic graphs.

Prerequisite:
- Good knowledge in data mining and machine learning
- Good knowledge in algorithm design
- Good programming skill (C++ or Java)

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
Design an algorithm to cluster dynamic graphs
Design an algorithm to trace cluster evolvement

(b) Development component
Implement the two algorithms
Evaluate on real dynamic graphs

472) Proj No. SCSE24-0485
Project Title How Accurate is NERD? Analyzing a Homonymous Author Name Disambiguation Framework
Project Summary Disambiguating author names in bibliographic databases is a challenging problem. A recent benchmarking study revealed that the semi-automatic approach adopted by DBLP is the state-of-the-art. However, homonymous author name disambiguation remains an unyielding problem in DBLP. Recently, we have developed a novel system called NERD to take a concrete step towards addressing this problem. We formalize this problem in DBLP as the namesake discovery problem (NDP) and present a light-weight and fast solution to address it.
Specifically, it exploits an external data source (i.e., OpenAlex) and deploys a non-machine learning-based solution to identify namesakes hidden in a DBLP page associated with an author name.

The goal of this project is to undertake exhaustive, rigorous, and systematic analysis of the results quality of NERD. To this end, real-world DBLP pages shall be used to analyze NERD’s ability to identify many namesakes accurately.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Analyze performance of NERD.

(b) Development component

Implement various performance metrics using Python.
Supervisor A/P Sourav Saha Bhowmick

Project Title Multilingual Translation for Cybersecurity Reports
Project Summary The multilingual nature of cybersecurity reports poses another challenge for the cybersecurity community in extracting cyber threat intelligence (CTI) from reports written in non-English languages. The existing machine translation model is designed for general-purpose and lacks an understanding of the cyber threat context. A customized machine translation model, which is capable of translating texts from non-English languages such as Chinese, Bahasa Indonesia, and Russian to English, is invaluable for CTI mining. Thus, this module aims to build a multilingual machine translation model that takes in cybersecurity data written in one of the three languages mentioned above and outputs the corresponding English translation.
To achieve this, we can use existing LLM-based models that support the capturing of cyber-related contextual information and machine translation. This project aims to find the most suitable pretrained BERT-based model that can handle the translations from Chinese to English, Bahasa Indonesia to English, and Russian to English. Thus, we need to build different AI-based models for machine translation from Chinese, Bhasha Indonesia, and Russian to English. As such, the translated contents of CTI reports can be used for the extraction of cyber-related events, entities, and relationships.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
To achieve this, we can use existing LLM-based models that support the capturing of cyber-related contextual information and machine translation. This project aims to investigate the most suitable pretrained BERT-based model that can handle the translations from Chinese to English, Bahasa Indonesia to English, and Russian to English. Thus, we need to build different AI-based models for machine translation from Chinese, Bhasha Indonesia, and Russian to English.

(b) Development component
The student will develop a machine translation model for translating Bahasa Indonesia to English (in particular), and evaluate the performance.

482) Proj No. SCSE24-0495
Project Title Edge/Cloud Resource Management for Time-Sensitive Applications (1)
Project Summary Cloud computing has become the default architecture of choice in many domains, primarily driven by the proliferation of compute-intensive Artificial Intelligence technologies. Orthogonally, with the increasing popularity of Internet-of-Things (IoT), decentralization of cloud computing in the form of edge and mobile computing is also happening. Although applications with time-critical functions have not yet been deployed on such architectures, this is rapidly changing with the advent of next-generation wireless technology like 5G. For example, such applications can be found in manufacturing (real-time robotic controls) and driving automation (localization using vehicle-to-infrastructure communication). In this project, we address the problem of energy-efficient resource allocations in such architectures, considering a mixed deployment of time-critical as well as non time-critical applications.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component: We will explore decentralized resource management techniques based on distributed consensus, a key technology from distributed systems. We will focus on provisioning problems (allocating servers and VMs to mobile workload) as well as scheduling problems (allocating CPU cycles and communication bandwidth over time).

(b) Development component: The developed strategies will be deployed on a edge/cloud simulation platform for evaluation purposes (CloudSim++).

483) Proj No. SCSE24-0496
Project Title Learning Latent Space Representation of Decision Trees for Interpretable RL
Project Summary Decision Trees (DTs) are widely used in machine learning because of their simplicity and interpretability. They have proven to be a powerful tool, especially in domains such as medicine, where the ability to explain the decision-making process is critical. However, training DTs in a Reinforcement Learning (RL) setting is challenging due to varying data during the agent's interaction with the environment. To address this challenge, much research work focuses on integrating DTs with Deep Neural Networks to train an interpretable model. In the project, we plan to investigate the integration of DTs with Transformers. Specifically, we plan to investigate the idea of generating a latent space representation of decision trees using transformers.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

Project objectives:
This project aims to provide a new perspective on how to improve RL agents' interpretability with the integration of DT and Transformer. The main objective of this project is to generate the latent space representation of decision trees using transformers and then use that latent representation to train RL policies.

Skills required:
   1. Python/Pytorch
2. Decision Trees and Deep Learning: It is necessary to have a basic understanding of Decision Trees and Deep Neural Networks.
3. NLP: Having some understanding of NLP concepts such as word embedding, RNN, Transformers, etc. can be beneficial for the project.
4. Reinforcement Learning: Acquiring a basic understanding of Reinforcement Learning will be beneficial to work on Task 3, which involves knowledge of Markov Decision Processes, Q-Learning, and Policy Gradient Methods.

484) Proj No. SCSE24-0497
Project Title State-of-the-art of AI integration methodologies & framework
Project Summary Project Intro
Currently, the integration of AI components is complex and requires ad-hoc developments that are error-prone and repetitive. The result can be systems that do not work as expected as an integrated whole. Indeed, it is not enough for the individual pieces to be functional in a software system. It is also key that their interfaces are well-defined, that components can communicate consistently for the integrated system to function as expected. For example, if one sub-system provides an unexpected input to the next system, that may lead to wrong behaviors and potential catastrophic failure.

Here we aim to evaluate the state-of-the-art of framework and methods available for the integration of AI systems and develop a simple application applying them.

Specific details:
Project objectives/tasks
Research existing methodologies for integration of AI models;
Evaluate their pro/cons;
Select one particular methodology and develop a prototype to show its functionalities and possibilities;
Evaluate strengths and weakness of the methodology proposed.

Skills required

Notions of AI;
Software engineering and interface design.

485) Proj No. SCSE24-0498
Project Title Guaranteed Hierarchical Reinforcement Learning
Project Summary Project Intro.:
Reinforcement learning is a training method for agents that utilizes the carrot-and-stick approach. It has been popularized through projects like AlphaGo and MuZero that have built agents capable of training themselves to perform better than humans in various environments. However, it is not always guaranteed to work and it can be very expensive when it does. Therefore, the aims of this project revolve around placing guarantees on the performance of the agent following the training process.


Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

Project objectives/tasks:
This project is primarily implementation based, though some research will be required. The focus of this project will be to use existing reinforcement learning algorithms to design and train a hierarchical RL system, where subtasks each have individual performance guarantees. Subsequently, the secondary objective is to evaluate the overall performance of the agent against the individual subtask guarantees.

Skills required:
The skills required for this project are as follows:
Basic understanding of probability theory/mathematics
Experience with Python
Experience with Tensorflow/Pytorch
Supervisor A/P Arvind Easwaran

486) Proj No. SCSE24-0499
Project Title Online Scheduling for Deadline-Constrained Applications in Edge-Cloud Systems
Project Summary Resource provisioning and scheduling for edge and cloud architecture have gained a lot of attention in the recent past both in academia and industry. This interest is primarily driven by the enormous success of two technologies in the field of computing: 1) Artificial intelligence (AI), and 2) Internet of Things (IoT). Cloud architectures play a central enabling role for AI due to the significant demand that this technology imposes on computation resources. Orthogonally, IoT has enabled an unprecedented decentralization and deployment of applications across application domains, including several in which AI is gaining prominence. As a result, the edge and cloud hardware architecture are poised to dominate the field of computing across application domains. A key challenge in this edge and cloud architecture is the efficient scheduling of time-critical applications while satisfying various constraints and optimization objectives.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

Project Objectives:
This is a research related project, which aims to address this challenge by developing decentralized and online scheduling algorithms that can provide deadline guarantees for time-sensitive applications while minimizing the power consumption of end devices and response time of non-time-sensitive applications. These capabilities will be enabling technology for the deployment of various safety-critical and time-sensitive applications across domains such as manufacturing, robotics, urban energy system, autonomous driving system, etc.

Skills Required:
Knowledge of Resource allocation or scheduling algorithms, convex/ILP problem optimization

492) Proj No. SCSE24-0505
Project Title Deep Reinforcement Learning for Resource Allocation in Wireless Networks
Project Summary This project delves into optimizing resource allocation in wireless networks, focusing on both communication resources, such as transmit power, and computational resources, notably caching capabilities within networks equipped with edge servers. Effective resource management is pivotal for enhancing critical performance indicators including the average achievable rate, energy efficiency, latency, and the Age of Information (AoI) of cached content. Traditional approaches often resort to conventional optimization techniques like convex optimization, which necessitate numerous assumptions and might result in suboptimal outcomes.
Deep Learning (DL) offers a potential improvement in performance; however, its application is hampered by the need for supervised learning datasets, which are challenging and computationally intensive to acquire, or sometimes, entirely unfeasible. Deep Reinforcement Learning (DRL) emerges as a solution to these challenges, capable of learning directly from the environment to optimize resource allocation strategies. By focusing on maximizing network performance metrics, DRL can dynamically adjust the resource allocation strategy, thus promising a more efficient and practical approach. This project aims to employ DRL to circumvent the limitations of traditional methods and datasets, optimizing resource allocation to achieve superior network performance metrics.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
Conduct a brief study on existing conventional and deep reinforcement learning (DRL) techniques for resource allocation in wireless communication. Investigate DRL techniques which can be adapted for the project

(b) Development component
Design and build a reinforcement learning environment for training the deep neural network by agent-environment interaction
Design and train the deep learning model with the environment
Evaluate the performance of the resulting DRL based resource allocation scheme
Supervisor A/P A S Madhukumar
Joint Industry Project/

Type Research & Development
Keywords Machine Learning
Wireless and Mobile Networks
493) Proj No. SCSE24-0506
Project Title Real-time multi-user beamforming using deep neural networks.
Project Summary In recent years, wireless communication systems have witnessed an unprecedented increase in the number of users and devices, leading to a demand for more efficient and adaptive beamforming techniques. Beamforming, a key technology in wireless communication, aims to enhance the signal quality by focusing the transmitted or received signals in specific directions. This project proposes the development of a real-time multi-user beamforming system using deep neural networks (DNNs) to address the challenges of interference mitigation and improved spectral efficiency.

This project will investigate dynamic beamforming while considering the user’s changing position and will use a deep learning framework to optimize the phase profile matrix used for accurate beamforming. The phase-shift matrix is a critical component of beamforming, and it is used to adjust the phase of the transmitted signals at each transmit element. A feedforward neural network with multiple layers will be used to learn the mapping between the channel state information (CSI) and the beamforming phase-shift matrix. The input to the network will be the propagation characteristics of the wireless channel, and the output will be the optimized phase-shift matrix. The goal of the network is to achieve a lightweight self-adaptive network with near real-time responses to changes in user locations. This will pave the way for the next generation of communication systems such as beyond 5G and 6G. Predicting the future location of the beams can be an extension to this work.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
The research phase involves a comprehensive literature review and the generation of channel state information (CSI) data from multiple users. This phase establishes the foundation for designing an effective DNN architecture that can optimize beamforming in a dynamic, multi-user wireless channel.

(b) Development component
The development phase encompasses the design and training of the DNN model, followed by its real-time implementation and integration into a multi-user beamforming system. Evaluation of the system's performance, focusing on interference reduction, signal quality enhancement, and spectral efficiency, will provide insights into the applicability and limitations of DNNs in this context. The final deliverables include a functional real-time system and a detailed report on the project's findings.
Supervisor A/P A S Madhukumar

505) Proj No. SCSE24-0518
Project Title Exploiting the Image Prior in CLIP for Super-Resolution
Project Summary Contrastive models like CLIP have achieved impressive success in learning image presentations supervised by natural language. It has been shown that the extracted image presentations are beneficial to the downstream vision tasks. In this project, we exploit how to harness the image knowledge in CLIP as prior to solve the task of image super-resolution. Specifically, a light network is designed to gradually fuse the features of the image encoder in CLIP and map them to the desirable high-quality image. During training, we tune the parameters in this network while fixing the image encoder of CLIP. In this way, it is capable of sufficiently leveraging the image prior of CLIP to facilitate the task of image super-resolution.


The student needs to have strong programming skills in Python. Motivated and independent.

Specific details:

508) Proj No. SCSE24-0521
Project Title protein design via constrained denoising diffusion probabilistic models
Project Summary The proposed research aims to develop a framework for constrained protein design using diffusion probabilistic models, to provide effective targets for potential applications such as therapeutics and protein engineering. Denoising diffusion probabilistic models (DDPM) are emerging as a powerful class of generative models in areas such as image and text to image synthesis (DALL-E 2, IMAGEN) [1, 2]. Recently, DDPM have been used to design protein backbones, as they allow effective sampling of novel protein folds [3],[4]. Although valuable, these methods contain several limitations, particularly in the applicability of the generated protein structures to real world scenarios, as such proteins do not meet the functional constraints, or chemical characteristics that pass the screen of applicable consideration.

Specific details:
To propose a framework that addresses the issue of incorporating functional constraints in an integrated way. The framework will also develop a library of constraints (site-specific mutation information and predicted docking energies) that can serve as special bias for protein design. This study builds upon our previous work incorporating prior knowledge of mutations of Influenza genomic sequence to build a predictive model [5].

The project utilizes Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs) and Natural Language Generation (NLG) technologies to automatically generate descriptive caption annotations for images, enhancing model text comprehension. 550) Proj No. SCSE24-0564
Project Title LLM Inference Serving Production Trace & System Performance Analysis
Project Summary The evolving domain of Large Language Models (LLM) has garnered attention worldwide, being utilized by a broad spectrum of users. Despite its widespread use, there remains an unexplored area due to the scarcity of data on how users interact with LLMs and how LLM inference services execute in a large-scale deployment, e.g., a GPU cluster. This initiative suggests the development of an online platform that delivers LLM services to a diverse audience free of charge. The main objective is to analyze the workload, i.e., queries and responses available in LLM inference trace patterns, and the implications of these patterrns in a GPU cluster setting.

The focus of this project is on the low-level computer systems part, requiring substantial motivation and effort to work at the software-hardware system interface, studying CPU, GPU, network, and disk usage patterns. The student will also be able to get more familiar with LLM inference workloads at the algorithmic level, and explore opportunities for co-designing the LLM system with the algorithm.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
- Investigate workload and trace characteristics to identify performance bottlenecks and areas for optimization.
- Study systems implications of LLM serving.
- Propose system optimizations to improve efficiency and responsiveness under dynamic load.

(b) Development component
- Implement a benchmarking framework to evaluate the MSaaS platform, focusing on GPU sharing efficiency and autoscaling in diverse real-world scenarios.
- Execute the evaluation methodology on an open-source LLM inference serving platform, such as KServe or RayServe, to gather performance metrics and validate the proposed optimizations.
- Incorporate the proposed system optimizations into the LLM inference serving platform, demonstrating improved GPU sharing efficiency and autoscaling capabilities for better resource utilization and scalability
Supervisor Ast/P Dmitrii Ustiugov
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No

Type Research & Development
Keywords Cloud Computing

Machine Learning

Project Title Real-Time Deep Learning-Based Image Matting for Mobile Devices
Project Summary This final year project focuses on developing a real-time, deep learning-based solution for image matting on mobile devices. The primary goal is to create an efficient algorithm capable of performing high-quality matting tasks in real-time on resource-constrained environments. Students will need a strong foundation in deep learning, specifically in techniques optimized for mobile platforms, and proficiency in Python programming. Knowledge of mobile computing and experience with optimization techniques for deep learning models, such as quantization and pruning, are crucial. The project will involve the design, implementation, and optimization of a neural network capable of handling the computational limitations of mobile devices while providing precise image matting results, thereby enabling advanced photo-editing capabilities directly from smartphones.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

a) Research Component: Investigate current deep learning-based image matting techniques and their performance on desktop environments. Identify the challenges and limitations when adapting these methods for mobile devices.
b) Development Component: Develop a lightweight, efficient deep learning model tailored for mobile platforms. This involves designing the architecture, optimizing the model for real-time performance on mobile devices, and implementing the solution in a mobile-friendly programming environment. The final product should deliver real-time image matting with minimal loss in quality.

Project Title Real-Time Monocular Depth Estimation on Mobile Devices Using Deep Learning
Project Summary This final year project aims to develop a robust, deep learning-based solution capable of estimating depth from monocular images in real time, specifically tailored for mobile devices. The challenge lies in achieving high accuracy and speed on devices with limited computational resources. Students must have a solid background in deep learning, computer vision, and proficiency in Python programming. Familiarity with mobile development frameworks and optimization techniques for deep learning models, such as model quantization and lightweight architecture design, is essential. The project entails designing, implementing, and optimizing a neural network that can efficiently perform depth estimation from single images on mobile platforms, enhancing applications in areas like augmented reality, photography, and navigation.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

a) Research Component: Examine existing deep learning methodologies for depth estimation from monocular images, focusing on their adaptability and efficiency on mobile devices. Identify gaps and opportunities for improvement in real-time performance and accuracy.
b) Development Component: Create and optimize a deep learning model suitable for mobile devices, prioritizing speed and efficiency without significantly compromising depth estimation accuracy. Implement the solution in a mobile application framework, ensuring it operates in real time and integrates seamlessly with mobile camera inputs.

604) Proj No. SCSE24-0618
Project Title Secure Fraud Detection: Leveraging Encrypted Learning on Private Datasets
Project Summary In the digital age, fraud detection has emerged as a paramount concern for financial institutions, e-commerce platforms, and various online services. However, the sensitive nature of financial and personal data often restricts direct access to these datasets for research and development purposes. This project proposes an innovative approach to learn from private datasets without direct access, ensuring both robust fraud detection and data privacy.

Utilizing techniques like Homomorphic Encryption and Secure Multi-party Computation, we aim to develop models that can be trained on encrypted data. This ensures that the raw data remains confidential and inaccessible, while still allowing the extraction of valuable patterns indicative of fraudulent activities. Additionally, we explore the potential of Federated Learning as a means to decentralize the training process, enabling multiple entities to collaboratively refine fraud detection models without sharing their datasets.

The primary objective is to strike a balance between the imperative need for effective fraud detection mechanisms and the ethical and legal requirements of data privacy. Preliminary results suggest that encrypted learning can indeed offer competitive performance in fraud detection scenarios, providing a viable alternative to traditional methods and setting the stage for a more secure and privacy-preserving future in financial analytics.

Specific details:
(a) Design component
To design an effective framework for fraud detection

(b) Implementation component
To implement privacy-preserving learning from distributed, privacy-sensitive datasets.

(b) Development component

607) Proj No. SCSE24-0621
Project Title Privacy leakage of federated fine-tuning
Project Summary Foundation models, characterized by their vast parameters and extensive pre-training on diverse datasets, have revolutionized various domains with their out-of-the-box performance. However, their deployment in real-world, on-device applications often faces challenges due to their sizable architecture and potential privacy concerns. Recently, a new framework for federated learning called promptFL has been proposed, which replaces the traditional federated model training with federated prompt training. In promptFL, federated participants train prompts instead of a shared model, leveraging the power of foundation models (FM) in a distributed way. The framework uses an off-the-shelf FM, CLIP, to train shared soft prompts based on limited local data. By updating only the prompts instead of the whole model, both local training and global aggregation can be accelerated. We observe that in promptFL, the client uploads parameter updates of the prompt learner directly to the server in plaintext. These updates must contain some private sample information, and it is possible to reconstruct the labels or even the original samples used by the user to generate the prompt by some special reconstruction means. In this regard, the student will learn how to carry out privacy attacks on user samples based on gradient of prompt learners, with the eventual hope of building privacy-preserving prompt learners.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component
To execute off-the-shelf prompt learning code and understand how they work in a federated way.

(a) Research component
To study the literature on prompt learning.

(b) Development component
Supervisor Ast/P Lim Wei Yang Bryan
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only
Type Research & Development
Keywords Artificial Intelligence

Project Title Federated fine-tuning of foundation AI models: Lightweight computing approaches
Project Summary Foundation models, characterized by their vast parameters and extensive pre-training on diverse datasets, have revolutionized various domains with their out-of-the-box performance. However, their deployment in real-world, on-device applications often faces challenges due to their sizable architecture and potential privacy concerns. This research delves into the concept of federated fine-tuning of these foundation models, aiming to produce "lightweight" versions suitable for decentralized applications. By leveraging federated learning, we propose a methodology to refine these models on local devices without centralized data pooling, ensuring data privacy. Preliminary results indicate that approaches can not only maintain competitive performance but also significantly reduce model size and computational overhead. This promises a new direction for the scalable and privacy-preserving deployment of foundation models in edge devices and beyond.
