Project Title Federated Learning meets Large Language Models: Adapting LLMs for privacy-sensitive downstream tasks
Project Summary In the era of expansive data and large language models (LLMs), ensuring user privacy without compromising the performance of models is of paramount importance. This project explores the integration of Federated Learning (FL) with LLMs to adapt them for privacy-sensitive downstream tasks. FL, a decentralized training approach, allows model training on user devices, ensuring data remains local. By integrating FL with LLMs, we aim to harness the power and capabilities of these models while upholding user data confidentiality. Preliminary results indicate a promising balance between model performance and privacy preservation, opening avenues for wide-scale, trustable, and efficient deployment of LLMs in privacy-critical applications.

Specific details:
(a) Design component
To develop an end-to-end pipeline for FL and LLM integeration.

(b) Implementation component
To develop a demo

(a) Research component


(b) Development component
To build on the efforts of supervisor's team during development

629) Proj No. SCSE24-0643
Project Title Semi-supervised learning and data harmonisation techniques for using deep learning models on multi-site neuroimaging data
Project Summary Large data sizes are necessary for analysis of high dimensional datasets such as neuroimaging data. However, these data often come in limited quantities (hundreds, or at most thousands). Data consortiums are thus formed to gather datasets from multiple imaging sites, but data cannot simply be combined together due to site differences and label inconsistency. We have previously developed a deep neural network architecture that performs data harmonisation and semi-supervised learning to deal with these issues (https://rdcu.be/cVD6Y). In this project, we will extend the architecture to improve the label harmonisation process, as well as explore the usefulness of integrating graph neural networks into the existing architecture. We will start from functional connectivity datasets on neurological diseases (e.g. Autism, ADHD) and thereafter validate our findings in other application areas. Throughout this project, the student will gain familiarity with deep learning frameworks such PyTorch. Also, the student will develop an in-depth understanding of GNN, data harmonisation techniques and semi-supervised learning.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component


(b) Development component
Supervisor Prof Jagath Chandana Rajapakse
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No
Category Software Only

630) Proj No. SCSE24-0644
Project Title Evaluating saliency of features in deep neural networks
Project Summary The ‘black-box’ nature of neural network is a barrier for adoption of neural networks for applications where interpretability is essential. Recently, there have been a few attempts to determine features that are most relevant and thereby interpret the prediction of neural networks. Recently, relevancy-backpropagation techniques have been introduced, which feedback the relevancy of output features to input features, to determine saliency of features. The goal of this project is to implement relevancy backpropagation techniques for selection of features and thereby develop novel techniques for pruning the neural networks.

The candidate will use pruned deep neural networks to classify genomic data. such as DNA sequences and gene expressions, from cancer patients and evaluate their performances. The candidate will thereby identify genes and mutations that are responsible for cancer.

The candidate will use Python and Tensorflow (https://www.tensorflow.org/).

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
The student will research on methods for evaluating saliency of features of neural networks and for pruning neural networks


(b) Development component
Student will develop routines to determine saliency of neural networks and prune neural networks in Python and tensorflow
Supervisor Prof Jagath Chandana Rajapakse
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No

638) Proj No. SCSE24-0652
Project Title Shortest Dubins Path for forward moving robots
Project Summary We study the problem of computing
optimal paths through three consecutive points for the
curvature-constrained forward moving Dubins vehicle. Given
initial and final configurations of the Dubins vehicle, and a
midpoint with an unconstrained heading, the objective is to
compute the midpoint heading that minimizes the total Dubins
path length. The additional constraint to consider is the speed of the robot on the various segments of the path.

Specific details:
(a) Design component
Design the algorithm to compute the three-point Dubins paths

(b) Implementation component
Coding and testing by simulation

641) Proj No. SCSE24-0655
Project Title Design and Implementation of Stress Detection System
Project Summary Stress is the body’s emotional response to a particular situation, where the body releases stress hormones such as adrenaline and cortisol which sharpen the body’s alertness and strength. Stress affects several physical processes in the autonomic nervous system (ANS) leading to increased muscle tension, change in concentration and changes in the heart rate and heart rate variability. New technologies have attempted to improve people’s quality of life in the last few years. Regarding the stress detection, methods and systems based on bio-signal analysis are under study. Outcomes:
• Improvisation of system which can acquire bio-signals (either ECG or EMG).
• Acquired bio-signal is analyzed for the detection of stress level using AI methods.

Specific details:
(a) Design component

A student attempting this project should improvise design and implement a device for real-time detection of stress level, based on the acquisition and analysis of bio-signals.

(b) Implementation component
Both the improvised hardware and software should be designed and implemented as a scope of this project.

Project Title Explainable multi-step time series forecasting model
Project Summary Time series forecasting is typically discussed where only a one-step prediction is required. Predicting multiple time steps into the future is called multi-step time series forecasting.
In a multi-step prediction, the model needs to learn to predict a range of future values. Thus, unlike a single-step model, where only a single future point is predicted, a multi-step model predicts a sequence of the values into the future.

Project Title Digitization of paper ECG using AI
Project Summary Electrocardiogram (ECG) is non-invasive, continental, and inexpensive and is currently one of the most commonly used diagnostic tools for cardiovascular diseases. The digitized ECG can be quickly, simultaneously measured and automatically interpreted, and complex ECG parameters can be measured, however, some ECGs are recorded by paper.
When the ECG is old and recorded only on paper reports, the scanning and digitization process is required. However, the defects of the scanned digitized ECG prevent direct waveform extraction from scans. Excessive noise and interference, patient information irrelevant to the ECG signal itself, and manual marking on the paper will affect the segmentation and analysis of the ECG. Digitizing the paper-based ECG records into a high-quality signal is critical for further analysis.

Project Title WebAssembly Performance Evaluation: Concurrency Focus (1)
Project Summary WebAssembly is the first new language to be introduced to the Web since JavaScript. It is intended to be a universal compilation target for the Web, enabling a variety of languages to be executed in Web sites.

WebAssembly currently aims to support compilation from C/C++ concurrency (threads and atomics) by re-using the existing features of JavaScript Web workers. This project will evaluate the performance of this approach through benchmarking.

Specific details:


(a) Research component

(b) Development component

Project Title Human contact data analysis
Project Summary Human contact interaction is one of the frequently observed forms of social activities, for instance, socialization in business meetings and exchange of ideas in conferences. Human contact interaction is also relevant to the spread of infectious diseases, such as influenza and COVID-19. Such infectious diseases might spread over by contact process among individuals in close-range physical proximity. Analyzing the contact process and its impact on the disease spread would be beneficial to better predict the patterns of disease spreading. This final year project aims at predicting potential disease spread using contact network dataset. From the dataset, the students will perform simulations of infectious disease transmission and identify potential hidden spreaders interacting with among the susceptible population without being detected or quarantined. Next, the student will study various scenarios based on different simulation setups in terms of disease transmission models and parameter setups.

Reference:
Huang, S., Sun, J., Feng, L., Xie, J., Wang, D. and Hu, Y. (2023) Identify hidden spreaders of pandemic over contact tracing networks. Scientific Reports, 13, 11621.

664) Proj No. SCSE24-0678
Project Title The impact of contact data resolution on disease transmission intervention strategy evaluations
Project Summary Modeling of infectious disease spread has received much attention recently mainly due to the current situation of COVID-19. A major approach in modeling disease spread is based on compartment models which assume well-mixed homogeneous populations. Such compartment models enable us to predict the infectious diseases spread in an aggregate level, which would be very useful for large-scale analysis. However, due to the nature of compartment models, the models have limitations on reflecting the contact process among individuals by which the diseases might spread over. High-resolution contact data can reflect details of contact interactions among individuals, but analyzing such contact data remains challenging mainly due to the data collection and computation cost. In this final year project, the students will examine the impact of contact data resolution on intervention strategy evaluations. Based on face-to-face empirical contacts datasets, the students will simulate infectious disease transmission and then and characteristics spreading dynamics for different data and network representations.

Reference:
Contreras, D.A., Colosi, E., Bassignana, G., Colizza, V. and Barrat, A. (2022) Impact of contact data resolution on the evaluation of interventions in mathematical models of infectious diseases. Journal of the Royal Society Interface, 19, 20220164.
https://royalsocietypublishing.org/doi/full/10.1098/rsif.2022.0164

Project Title Simulation Modelling of AI Clusters
Project Summary The performance of AI clusters can be affected by various factors, such as model parameters, workload distribution, job scheduler logic, topology, and hardware specifications. Such a framework will facilitate comprehensive design and optimization across different system levels and support data-driven decision-making in AI cluster design. In this project, the student will review existing research on simulating AI clusters, with a particular focus on AI workload modelling.

Project Title IntrinsicDiff: Extracting Intrinsic Image Components from Diffusion Models
Project Summary The current generative models are already capable of generating highly realistic and high-quality images. But what is the extent of these models' understanding of images? Have they learned the intrinsic properties of images, and can we extract them? Intrinsic properties of images, including normal maps, depth maps, shading, and albedo, can greatly assist in image editing. For example, we can use a normal map to change the lighting of an image. This project will explore how to extract these components using LORA from diffusion models (including SD 1.5, 2.1, XL, and diffusion transformers) and further enhance the quality of the output intrinsics.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

1. Reproduce the existing work and evaluate the quality of the results.
2. Extending the method onto Stable Diffusion-XL and Diffusion Transformers.
3. Try to use some training-free tricks to further improve the quality of the extracted intrinsic properties.

(b) Development component

1. Develop a Web UI to let user upload their images and do the decomposition easily.
2. Support some downstream tasks, like relighting, in the interactive interface.
Supervisor Ast/P Pan Xingang

URECA FYP? 		No

Keywords Artificial Intelligence

674) Proj No. SCSE24-0691
Project Title DragAny3D: Interactive Point-Dragging Manipulation for 3D Objects via 2D Diffusion Prior
Project Summary The realm of 3D model editing through generative artificial intelligence (AI) has recently gained considerable attention. While current methods for 3D editing offer support for tasks such as text-based texture editing (e.g., Instruct-NeRF2NeRF) or point-based local 3D geometry deformation (e.g., CNS-Edit and APAP), they often encounter difficulties in precisely controlling geometry or realistically generating new content. In this project, our aim is to develop an approach that enables interactive point-dragging manipulation of any 3D object, facilitating the generation of new content (including both geometry and texture) during the dragging process. This initiative is inspired by a series of recent drag-based image editing techniques (e.g., DragGAN, DragDiffusion, and DragonDiffusion), which have shown promising results in the realm of 2D image manipulation. Our goal is to extend these methods to 3D objects. By doing so, we aim to empower users to deform 3D objects with precise control over the placement of keypoints, thus allowing for the manipulation of various attributes such as shape and texture while ensuring fidelity to the original object. This extension promises a more intuitive and versatile approach to 3D model editing, opening up possibilities for a wide range of applications and creative endeavors.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

The point-dragging 3D manipulation algorithm involves two main components: multi-view 2D editing and consistent 3D reconstruction. We will first use established 2D drag-based editing techniques to produce multi-view dragged results. Then, leveraging these 2D results, we will use 3D Gaussian Splatting to reconstruct view-consistent 3D objects. Finally, these two techniques will be seamlessly integrated into a system.

(b) Development component

To achieve our goal, we need to first reproduce the DragDiffusion (or DragonDiffusion) method and the 3D Gaussian Splatting method, which is a 3D reconstruction approach. We will then implement our 3D point-dragging algorithm based on these two approaches. Finally, a GUI should be developed which allows users to easily input 3D control points and target points, and to monitor the editing process.

675) Proj No. SCSE24-0692
Project Title DragDIT: Interactive Point-Dragging Manipulation in Diffusion Transformer
Project Summary The success of DragGAN has sparked interest in exploring point-dragging manipulation using diffusion models. However, current attempts fall short compared to GANs, mainly due to the lack of a compact semantic latent space in diffusion models. The emergence of Diffusion Transformer (DiT) has garnered attention for its superior model capacity and learning efficiency compared to Conv U-Net-based diffusion models. Notably, DiT's unique characteristics hold promise for enhancing point-dragging manipulation. With the release of large-scale pretrained text-to-image DiT models, there is an opportunity to extend the DragGAN algorithm and integrate it with DiT. This collaboration may unlock new capabilities and potentially lead to improved point-dragging manipulation.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

We will develop a point-dragging manipulation algorithm specifically tailored for Diffusion Transformer. Drawing inspiration from methods like DragGAN and DragDiffusion, our algorithm will inherit key principles while incorporating necessary modifications for seamless compatibility with Diffusion Transformer. This approach aims to leverage the strengths of existing techniques while optimizing them for enhanced performance within the context of Diffusion Transformer models.

(b) Development component

We will first implement a vanilla point-dragging manipulation algorithm for a pretrained text-to-image DiT. This will include a motion supervision component and a point-tracking component. Then we will do modification to optimize the algorithm specifying to DiT. Additionally, we'll develop a user-friendly GUI for easy interaction.

676) Proj No. SCSE24-0693
Project Title Human Pose Transfer via Pre-trained Text-to-Image Models
Project Summary Human pose transfer remains a captivating area of study due to its broad applications in image production and everyday life. The primary challenge is to maintain the integrity of the target postures and the visual appearances of the humans. Recently, large text-to-image models have shown its superior capability in image generation and editing. Some previous works utilize additional conditions, e.g., human skeletons, to direct the image generation process, ensuring generated human postures aligned with the conditions. Another methodology incorporates an image prompt encoder to retain the visual appearances from conditional images, allowing the resulting images to mirror the appearances of the conditions closely. By combining these techniques, it's possible to preserve both the fidelity of postures and the visual identity of humans, culminating in effective human pose transfer. This research delves into the potential of pre-trained text-to-image models for facilitating human pose transfer.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Utilize skeleton generation techniques to obtain skeletons from human images and form a paired dataset for training. 2) Investigate a conditioning mechanism that incorporates skeletons into the pre-trained text-to-image model. 3) Investigate an approach to incorporate image prompts into the pre-trained text-to-image model to preserve the visual appearances of humans.

(b) Development component

1) Develop a Web User Interface for users to input human images and target postures, and view the generated results 2) Implement a human pose transfer model via a pre-trained text-to-image model using the proposed method.

679) Proj No. SCSE24-0696
Project Title Profiler for RocksDB
Project Summary RocksDB stands as a prevalent LSM-tree key-value store system, often serving as an embedded key-value store for various applications. Typically, RocksDB gathers statistical data, including operation execution times and internal event occurrences, and provides this information cumulatively through functions such as statistics.ToString or statistics.getHistogramString. While these functions deliver a comprehensive report up to the current point, the need often arises to analyze data within specific time windows or perform complex real-time calculations on internal events, a process known as stream processing.

In industry settings, streaming systems like ElasticSearch, Prometheus, and Kafka are commonly employed to collect internal statistical data from database systems. This enables developers and database administrators (DBAs) to monitor events and computations dynamically in real-time. However, RocksDB faces limitations in this regard due to the absence of relevant interfaces. It can only accumulate statistical data in memory and process them in batch, posing challenges for real-time monitoring.

Specific details:
Your task is to implement a new class extending the Statistics interface in RocksDB which is able to:

1. Collect statistical data for internal events or operations
2. Emit the statistics by stream to a streaming system (e.g., push data to a Prometheus instance)
3. Support common stream processing and windowing

(a) Research component


(b) Development component
Supervisor Ast/P Luo Siqiang

URECA FYP? 		No

Type Design & Implementation
Keywords Data Analytics

704) Proj No. SCSE24-0721
Project Title Exploring the Design of Diffusion Models
Project Summary Diffusion Models have achieved great success in image synthesis in recent years. In diffusion models, a U-Net is used to denoise a Gaussian noise for multiple steps and the U-Net is usually conditioned on the denoising time t. However, in different denoising steps, the function of the U-Net might be different. For example, in early denoising steps, it mainly focuses on generating the global layout, while in layer denoising steps, it focuses on generating details. This project will study different design choices to introduce the time (denoising step t) conditioning. For example, we will study the use of different model weights for different denoising steps.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

We will study different design choices to introduce the time (denoising step t) conditioning in diffusion models. For example, we will study the use of different model weights for different denoising steps.

(b) Development component

We will first implement a diffusion model code base and train a diffusion model on an image dataset to perform image synthesis. Next, we will implement the different design choices we are interested, and compare the results.
Supervisor Ast/P Pan Xingang

Project Title Models for Privacy-preserving Image Super-resolution.
Project Summary Learning based models are known to be susceptible to adversarial attacks, in which adding small perturbations in the clean input image will lead a classifier to make wrong predictions. Adversarial images usually bring threats to practical deep learning applications such as autonomous driving, safety surveillance, and intelligent healthcare. However, it has positive value in privacy-preserving applications, such as the application of photo sharing in social media toward cyber security.

In this project, we will explore generative models to generate adversarial examples for Image super-resolution tasks. Generated adversarial images can attack malicious recognition systems yet preserve the information of the original low-resolution input image. Recently, diffusion models have been explored for image super-resolution tasks without considering privacy-preserving (https://openaccess.thecvf.com/content/CVPR2023/html/Gao_Implicit_Diffusion_Models_for_Continuous_Super-Resolution_CVPR_2023_paper.html), and in this project, we will explore new methods to preserve privacy for image super-resolution.

(b) Implementation component

Project Title Resource- and Energy-efficient Deep Learning Models for 3D Data Analysis
Project Summary Deep learning with 3D data is vital for a wide range of emerging applications such as autonomous driving, robot perception, VR/AR, UAV inspection, and 3D metrology. However, due to the unique characteristics of 3D data, as well as the hard constraints from real-world applications, the research and adoption of 3D deep learning are currently facing many technical challenges such as high storage & computation costs, high power consumption, high latency, etc. This proposal aims to develop fundamental 3D deep learning data analysis techniques, specifically developing resource-efficient and energy-efficient 3D deep learning models to tackle the challenges occurred in current 3D models, such as huge memory & computation costs and huge power consumption, to make 3D deep learning more realistic for real-world applications.

Objective: The primary goal of this research is to design novel compression algorithms (quantization, pruning, entropy coding, etc.) for state-of-the-art 3D deep learning models. The proposed approach should be able to significantly reduce the size of 3D models, reduce the computation operations, and lower the power consumption, without hurting the accuracy. The proposed method will be evaluated on mainstream 3D detection models (Voxel-RCNN, F-PointNet) at public benchmark datasets (Kitti, Nuscene).

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component

Data Collection and Preprocessing: Gather and preprocess a tiny dataset for ablation study. Explore techniques for data reduction, quantization, and feature engineering to minimize data requirements.

Finetuning: Finetune (retrain) compressed models using a tiny dataset (or even without using any data). Finetune the models to achieve high accuracy while using as less training data as possible.

(b) Development component

Literature Review: Conduct a comprehensive review of 3D data analysis models (3D detection models, 3D point clouds, etc.) and model compression techniques (post-train quantization, structured pruning, etc.). Identify relevant methodologies and best practices for designing compression algorithm for 3D models.

Benchmarking and Evaluation: Conduct rigorous benchmarking and evaluation of the accuracy of compressed models after finetuning. Report the results on standard public datasets and compare with state-of-the-arts

727) Proj No. SCSE24-0744
Project Title A Software Tool for Approximate Computing Hardware for use in Safety-Critical Applications
Project Summary Safety-critical applications such as space systems are resource-constrained and are expected to be low-power and energy-efficient. However, using a single functional unit (where a functional unit may be an electronic circuit or system) is not practical in a space system since the failure of the sole functional unit due to harsh environmental conditions (such as radiation) would be catastrophic causing a mission failure. Therefore, the functional unit used in say a space system should be able to cope with harsh environments by remaining tolerant to likely fault(s) or failure(s). To ensure fault tolerance, redundancy is usually employed as a radiation hardening-by-design approach whereby multiple copies of a functional unit are used instead of a single functional unit to cope with the fault(s) or failure(s) of one or more functional unit(s) and still guarantee the correct operation. While low power and energy efficiency are expected for a space system, the use of multiple copies of a functional unit would tend to increase the design metrics such as area, delay, power, and energy – this presents a dichotomy. To manage this dichotomy, in this project, approximate computing is considered a new design paradigm for realizing redundancy with approximate but acceptable functional units to reduce the design metrics of conventional redundancy incorporating accurate functional units and simultaneously ensuring fault tolerance. A software tool to automatically generate approximate computing hardware from accurate computing hardware already exists (which is open-access) and this project would develop and provide an add-on to the tool to automatically generate redundant approximate computing hardware from accurate computing hardware depending on an application requirement. The redundant approximate computing hardware autogenerated could be used to demonstrate its usefulness for say, digital image processing, which is commonplace in space systems.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
This will involve developing add-on software for an application which was performed by an FYP student a couple of years ago.
That student achieved 1 journal and 2 conference publications from that work.

(b) Development component
Supervisor A/P Douglas Leslie Maskell
Joint Industry Project/
URECA FYP? 		No

Type Research & Development
Keywords Programming Languages & Systems
Software and Applications
728) Proj No. SCSE24-0745
Project Title Approximate Computing for Machine Learning
Project Summary Approximate computing is considered to be an alternative to accurate computing for many practical applications which are inherently error tolerant. Examples of such applications include hardware realization of deep neural networks for machine learning and artificial intelligence, low-power graphics processing, neuromorphic computing, digital image/video/audio processing, memory systems for multicore processors, big data and analytics, etc. This project intends to explore the suitability of approximate computing for a machine learning application. In this context, K-means clustering, which is a popular unsupervised machine learning algorithm that is widely used for cluster analysis in data mining such as computer graphics, image classification, etc. is considered a candidate for approximation. The objective of K-means clustering is to group similar data points into K clusters by dividing the data into different categories based on an analysis of the underlying patterns; K is the number of cluster centroids, each of which is the location representing the center of a cluster in a dataset. While clustering, a data point is allocated to each cluster by reducing the within-cluster sum of squares (WCSS). The WCSS value is the sum of distances between each data point and the centroids. A low WCSS value implies better clustering. Typically, the WCSS value is computed accurately. This project intends to investigate the potential of approximate computing by computing the WCSS value for the clustering based on different approximate addition architectures presented in the existing literature and compare it with the accurate computation. To perform the experimentation, open-source artificial or real-world datasets can be considered. Further, the possibility of developing a new approximate addition architecture for machine learning would be considered.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
explore the suitability of approximate computing for a machine learning application

(b) Development component
Supervisor A/P Douglas Leslie Maskell
Joint Industry Project/

Type Research & Development

Project Title Foundation Model Security
Project Summary Foundation Models are large-scale AI models trained on vast amounts of data. However, their immense size, complexity, and the quality of training data pose various security or privacy leak challenges. For example, the vast size and complexity of these models pose challenges for humans to explain their inner workings clearly, resulting in some degree of uninterpretability. Additionally, large datasets may contain sensitive information, and malicious users might be able to deduce such information by analyzing the model's output. This project aims to focus on identifying potential attack surfaces or privacy leaks in these models, alerting the security community to threats, and formulating secure strategies for development and deployment.

This project demands a high level of sophistication. Participating students are expected to possess a comprehensive background in deep learning along with strong programming skills.

734) Proj No. SCSE24-0751
Project Title Secure and Efficient General Matrix Multiplication On Cloud Using Homomorphic Encryption
Project Summary Cloud computing offers significant technical and financial benefits but is often met with skepticism regarding security and privacy concerns, especially among entities like government agencies and commercial sectors with stringent security needs. Homomorphic Encryption (HE) presents a promising solution to these concerns by enabling computations on encrypted data, thus preserving privacy and security for sensitive applications. Despite its potential, the practical application of HE is hampered by its prohibitive computational costs, which are significantly higher than those of plaintext-based computations.
This project will address the challenge of optimizing HE-based computations for general Matrix Multiplication (MM), a critical operation underlying many practical applications. By leveraging the Single Instruction Multiple Data (SIMD) operations supported by HE schemes, we will introduce a novel element-wise algorithm tailored for efficient matrix multiplication. Building on this foundation, we will propose Homomorphic Encryption-based General Matrix Multiplication (HEGMM) algorithms designed to minimize computational overhead.
We will conduct rigorous experimental evaluations to demonstrate that the proposed HEGMM algorithms substantially outperform existing methods for HE-based matrix multiplication. The advancements in this project will not only contribute to reducing the computational costs associated with Homomorphic Encryption but also broaden the horizon for its application in security-sensitive sectors, marking a step forward in resolving the privacy-security paradox in cloud computing.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component
we will introduce a novel element-wise algorithm tailored for efficient matrix multiplication.

(b) Development component
We will conduct rigorous experimental evaluations to demonstrate that the proposed Homomorphic Encryption-based General Matrix Multiplication (HEGMM) algorithms substantially outperform existing methods for HE-based matrix multiplication.

735) Proj No. SCSE24-0752
Project Title Uncertainty-Based Cancer Screening
Project Summary This project investigates the efficacy of various uncertainty estimation algorithms in predicting cancer risks. This project aims to explore how uncertainty quantification techniques, such as Bayesian neural networks, ensemble methods, or dropout regularization, can enhance cancer screening models. By assessing uncertainty in predictions, the project seeks to improve the reliability and interpretability of cancer risk assessments. Through rigorous evaluation and comparison of different uncertainty estimation approaches, the project aims to identify the most effective methods for guiding screening decisions and informing patients about the confidence levels associated with their cancer risk predictions.

(b) Implementation component

741) Proj No. SCSE24-0758
Project Title Using Large Language Models (LLMs) for Low-Resource Languages
Project Summary In our globally interconnected world, many languages face the risk of extinction. Low-resource languages, which have limited available digital text data, encounter numerous challenges in technology integration. This proposal outlines a project that aims to develop and implement Large Language Models (LLMs) specifically tailored for low-resource languages, thereby promoting language preservation and ensuring equitable access to cutting-edge language technologies for all.

Objectives:
Develop LLMs for Low-Resource Languages: Construct and refine LLMs to work effectively with specific low-resource languages.

Leverage Transfer Learning: Use high-resource languages to bolster model performance for low-resource languages.
Data Augmentation: Enhance limited datasets through innovative data augmentation techniques.

Promote Language Preservation: Aid in the preservation and revitalization of endangered and low-resource languages.
Proposed Methodology:

Phase 1: Preliminary Research and Collaboration

Conduct a comprehensive analysis to identify the specific needs and challenges of the target low-resource languages.
Establish collaborations with linguistic experts and communities for insights and data collection.

Phase 2: Model Development

Transfer Learning: Initiate model pretraining on high-resource languages followed by fine-tuning on low-resource language data.

Data Augmentation: Augment datasets through translation, back-translation, and synthetic data generation.
Custom Architectures: Design and implement neural network architectures optimized for low-resource languages.

Phase 3: Model Evaluation and Refinement

Evaluate the models’ performance rigorously and iteratively refine them for optimal results.
Gather feedback from native speakers and experts for further improvements.

Phase 4: Implementation and Integration

Deploy the developed LLMs for real-world applications including translation and sentiment.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component


(b) Development component
Supervisor Ast/P Zhao Jun

Type Research & Development

745) Proj No. SCSE24-0762
Project Title Artificial Intelligence (AI) Foundation Models Research
Project Summary 1. Introduction

Foundation models, like GPT-4 and BERT, have transformed our ability to generate and process text, images, and more. However, while their capabilities are vast, so too are the challenges and questions they present. This proposal aims to conduct in-depth research into the various facets of foundation models, examining their potential, their limitations, and their broader impact on society.

2. Objectives

Understanding Model Behavior: Delve into the intricacies of foundation models to decipher their decision-making processes and understand their generated outputs.

Ethical Implications: Explore the ethical dimensions of these models, including concerns about biases, misinformation, and their potential for misuse.

Optimization and Efficiency: Investigate methods to optimize training processes, reduce computational costs, and make models more accessible.

3. Methodology

Literature Review: A thorough examination of current literature to understand the state-of-the-art and identify gaps in knowledge.

Experimental Analysis: Setting up controlled experiments to understand the behavior of foundation models under various conditions.

Stakeholder Interviews: Engaging with end-users, developers, and ethicists to gain diverse perspectives on the use and implications of foundation models.

(b) Implementation component

747) Proj No. SCSE24-0764
Project Title 360-Degree Video Streaming in the Metaverse: Tailored Reinforcement Learning Strategies
Project Summary In the dynamic and rapidly evolving landscape of the Metaverse, the pivotal challenge of delivering
optimal Quality of Service (QoS) for 360-degree video streaming stands at the forefront of virtual reality
technology. This challenge becomes increasingly complex when addressing the diverse needs of both
Virtual Reality (VR) and non-VR users. Deep Reinforcement Learning (DRL), particularly Proximal Policy
Optimization (PPO) and Separate Input Differentiated Output (SIDO), presents a promising approach to
tackle this challenge. Our exploration delves into the integration of these advanced techniques,
revealing SIDO's superior performance with a striking enhancement over conventional PPO
methods. This significant improvement is rooted in SIDO's adept handling of the varied QoS demands,
ensuring high frame rates and low latency for VR users, while maintaining resource efficiency for non-VR
users. Our findings not only underscore the efficacy of customized DRL strategies in managing the
intricacies of virtual environments but also open new avenues for future innovation. This research paves
the way for further exploration into algorithmic refinement, adaptation to diverse scenarios within the
Metaverse, real-world application testing, and incorporating user feedback for QoS personalization. As
we venture into this uncharted digital realm, our work establishes a foundation for more immersive,
efficient, and user-focused virtual experiences, signifying a significant leap in the domain of 360-degree
video streaming technology.

Specific details:
(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component


(b) Development component
Supervisor Ast/P Zhao Jun

Type Research & Development

748) Proj No. SCSE24-0765
Project Title Web3 Edge Computing: A Study on the Integration of Decentralized Computing and Edge Computing in the Web3 Ecosystem
Project Summary Introduction:
Web3 has the potential to change the way we interact with the internet. With its decentralized architecture, Web3 provides a new level of security and control for users. One of the key components of Web3 is edge computing, which allows for data processing and computation to occur closer to the user. Edge computing offers a number of benefits, including improved performance, reduced latency, and enhanced security. However, the integration of edge computing and decentralized computing in Web3 presents its own set of challenges. In this proposal, we will explore the potential of Web3 edge computing and identify areas for further research to optimize its integration in the Web3 ecosystem.

Research Questions:

What is the current state of Web3 edge computing, and how does it differ from traditional edge computing?
What are the potential benefits and challenges of integrating decentralized computing and edge computing in Web3?
How can Web3 developers design applications that leverage edge computing to improve performance and security?
How can Web3 edge computing be used to enable new use cases, such as IoT and autonomous vehicles?
Methodology:
This study will utilize a mixed-methods approach, including both quantitative and qualitative data collection methods. We will conduct a systematic review of existing literature on Web3 edge computing, including academic articles, whitepapers, and technical reports. Additionally, we will conduct interviews with Web3 developers and industry experts to gain insights into the challenges and opportunities for integrating edge computing in the decentralized web. We will also analyze Web3 applications to identify areas for improvement in terms of leveraging edge computing for improved performance and security.

(a) Design component


(b) Implementation component

(a) Research component


(b) Development component

752) Proj No. SCSE24-0769
Project Title Federated learning study
Project Summary Federated Learning is a hot topic in the recent years due to the increased emphasis for data privacy. Therefore, with less accessibility to restricted private data, federated learning is designed to bring the deep learning models to the private data for anonymous training. However, with increasingly complex model architecture, large latency during model transfer can be induced and model training can take up a lot of time. Therefore, to solve this, we would like to suggest adaptations to the conventional federated learning process. In this project, students will research on different adaptation techniques to the conventional federated learning. This can include deep reinforcement learning for model pruning to reduce the complex model's size.

Specific details:

federated learning framework

(b) Implementation component
federated learning framework

(a) Research component
differential privacy technique
